WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:55.656 --> 00:00:56.539
[jazz music]

00:01:00.137 --> 00:01:03.050
[Peter] Toby, Jacob,
I've been waiting for this one.

00:01:03.117 --> 00:01:04.984
-We've got the bikes down there.
-Yep.

00:01:05.051 --> 00:01:08.508
We're gonna rip around town.
Learn it through the eyes of the locals.

00:01:08.575 --> 00:01:11.806
-People are coming from all over the world
to Northwest Arkansas.

00:01:11.873 --> 00:01:15.306
This is the biggest collector of talent.
It's very intentional here.

00:01:15.373 --> 00:01:17.275
Everything you see here, from the art,

00:01:17.342 --> 00:01:19.983
from the coffee,
the live music, the trail system,

00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:23.110
is to attract and retain
millennials and Gen Z.

00:01:23.177 --> 00:01:25.142
-Bike trail system?
-Bike trail system.

00:01:25.209 --> 00:01:29.316
We have 500 miles of bike trail
from greenway to singletrack.

00:01:29.650 --> 00:01:32.959
USA Cycling's mountain bike,
and cross-country teams train here.

00:01:33.026 --> 00:01:34.835
There's a lot of tourists as well.

00:01:34.902 --> 00:01:39.305
Okay. And so Jacob, who I thought
was your brother, is your son.

00:01:39.372 --> 00:01:41.172
-That's right.
-So good work on that.

00:01:41.239 --> 00:01:44.409
Good work on aging. So it has to do with
the biking here, maybe.

00:01:44.476 --> 00:01:47.979
This is very outdoorsy here.
The culture is kind of Colorado.

00:01:48.046 --> 00:01:51.275
It's very mountainous,
there are a lot of outdoorsy people here,

00:01:51.342 --> 00:01:53.380
and people are attracted
to active lifestyle.

00:01:53.447 --> 00:01:56.865
Bentonville was
a 3,000-person town in the 1990s.

00:01:56.932 --> 00:01:58.297
-How many is it now?

00:01:58.364 --> 00:02:01.688
-65,000, but the metro is around 620,000.

00:02:01.755 --> 00:02:04.570
-And we're passing a million next decade.
-That's crazy.

00:02:04.637 --> 00:02:05.520
Yep.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:09.225
[Peter] So this building,
we're biking on it.

00:02:09.292 --> 00:02:11.019
-Biking up the building and down.

00:02:11.086 --> 00:02:14.302
The Ledger is the first
bikeable building in the United States.

00:02:14.376 --> 00:02:18.620
There is a exoskeleton that doubles
as a trail all the way to the roof.

00:02:18.687 --> 00:02:20.522
-Exoskeleton?
-Yeah.

00:02:20.589 --> 00:02:23.243
-So we're wrapping around the building?
-That's right.

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:24.220
This is awesome.

00:02:24.287 --> 00:02:27.541
-And we have public art everywhere,
including these medallions.

00:02:27.608 --> 00:02:30.303
These are bugs and jewels
native to Arkansas.

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:33.370
This trail goes from
the seventh story to the floor.

00:02:33.930 --> 00:02:36.048
-So when you get out in the country,

00:02:36.749 --> 00:02:39.219
when you travel and you say,
I'm from Arkansas,

00:02:39.286 --> 00:02:40.815
what's the standard reply?

00:02:41.785 --> 00:02:43.983
If I say Arkansas, I'll get an eye roll.

00:02:44.050 --> 00:02:46.395
If I say Bentonville,
people are starting to perk up.

00:02:46.462 --> 00:02:48.343
-They get it?
-Yep.

00:02:48.410 --> 00:02:50.345
Oh, that's beautiful. Look at that.

00:02:50.412 --> 00:02:51.295
-Yep.

00:02:51.750 --> 00:02:53.515
Looks like a co-working space.

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:57.223
Oh, these are some nice old homes here.

00:02:57.290 --> 00:02:59.923
Jacob, what's the price
on something like that?

00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:03.092
-I would say 1.8,
close to 2 for this location.

00:03:03.159 --> 00:03:04.452
-Oh, geez.

00:03:04.533 --> 00:03:07.387
-These are all new, these buildings?
-It's a new hotel.

00:03:07.454 --> 00:03:10.446
From the ledger to the moto
to a lot of these new buildings,

00:03:10.513 --> 00:03:12.292
this is all in the last five years.

00:03:12.359 --> 00:03:14.167
-Okay, nice, bougie.

00:03:14.234 --> 00:03:16.361
Are you gonna call it bougie? Fair to say?

00:03:16.428 --> 00:03:20.413
There's even signs that say,
keep Bentonville bougie. [chuckles]

00:03:21.170 --> 00:03:23.820
Bentonville started out
as an apple orchard town,

00:03:23.887 --> 00:03:26.547
but Sam Walton moved here
after World War II.

00:03:26.614 --> 00:03:30.137
And in 1950, started
the Walton Five and Dime right here.

00:03:30.204 --> 00:03:34.643
In 1962, he opened his actual first Walmart
in Rogers, the next town over.

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:37.081
He changed retail forever.

00:03:37.148 --> 00:03:40.649
He was the richest man in the world
and he still was driving this Ford.

00:03:40.716 --> 00:03:44.304
-This is a Walmart museum?
-Yeah. Gonna walk right on through.

00:03:49.056 --> 00:03:52.821
-Are there some Walmart lovers out there,
like true patriots to Walmart?

00:03:52.888 --> 00:03:56.700
Yeah. So Walmart's really shifted
its focus to its associates.

00:03:56.767 --> 00:03:59.136
If you work at Walmart
after a number of years

00:03:59.203 --> 00:04:01.070
you get invited to corporate.

00:04:01.137 --> 00:04:03.359
So, half of the employees
are international,

00:04:03.426 --> 00:04:05.411
and half are here in the United States,

00:04:05.478 --> 00:04:07.826
and they come from all over
to the mothership.

00:04:07.893 --> 00:04:10.665
-The mothership?
And that's the original office?

00:04:10.732 --> 00:04:12.800
-Yeah, that's Sam's original office.

00:04:12.867 --> 00:04:13.750
-Interesting.

00:04:14.821 --> 00:04:16.503
Oh, and this goes on for a ways.

00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:20.618
-Yeah, it tells the whole story,
going from 1 to 10,000 Walmarts.

00:04:21.063 --> 00:04:22.779
-First products of Walmart.

00:04:22.846 --> 00:04:24.453
-Walmart is still fortune one.

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:28.181
This is the largest company in the world
in revenue and employee count.

00:04:28.248 --> 00:04:30.704
-I didn't know that.
-Yes. This is Fortune one.

00:04:30.771 --> 00:04:33.006
-Bigger than NVIDIA?
-In terms of revenue, yep.

00:04:33.073 --> 00:04:34.803
Profits no, revenue, yes?

00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:37.040
-Yes. Very thin margins with Walmart.

00:04:37.107 --> 00:04:38.645
-So this is Sam?
-Yep.

00:04:38.712 --> 00:04:40.451
He was a hunter and a fisher.

00:04:40.518 --> 00:04:42.935
-He's just an everyday guy.
-Just a good old boy.

00:04:43.002 --> 00:04:44.984
Yep. Hunting with Jimmy Carter.

00:04:45.051 --> 00:04:47.623
Two more floors. Keeps on going. Okay.

00:04:49.990 --> 00:04:52.158
So there's a lot of history in Bentonville.

00:04:52.225 --> 00:04:55.465
This road right here
was the original Trail of Tears.

00:04:55.532 --> 00:04:58.653
-For the Cherokee?
-Yeah, 1830s, they came through here.

00:04:58.734 --> 00:05:01.384
You're only 20 miles
from Cherokee Nation in Oklahoma.

00:05:01.451 --> 00:05:04.522
-I've been to the Eastern Band of Cherokee.
It's actually really nice.

00:05:04.589 --> 00:05:06.248
There was also a Civil War battle

00:05:06.315 --> 00:05:09.333
just outside of Bentonville
right down this road.

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:11.723
So one industry
totally changed the landscape?

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:12.690
Thousand percent.

00:05:12.757 --> 00:05:14.899
One industry, that because of Walmart,

00:05:14.966 --> 00:05:18.061
every major brand in the world
has an office here.

00:05:19.046 --> 00:05:20.829
-What I'm liking about this,

00:05:20.896 --> 00:05:23.671
You guys are comfortable
leaving your expensive e-bikes.

00:05:23.738 --> 00:05:24.808
That's exactly right.

00:05:24.875 --> 00:05:26.810
We can leave this here and come back.

00:05:26.877 --> 00:05:27.934
All right. Cool.

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:31.531
So as we open up the Walmart story today,

00:05:31.598 --> 00:05:33.925
-I got some pressing questions, okay?
-You bet.

00:05:33.992 --> 00:05:36.642
I want to make sure
the audience doesn't think this is

00:05:36.709 --> 00:05:38.059
a Walmart propaganda video.

00:05:38.126 --> 00:05:40.379
This town is way beyond
Walmart at this point.

00:05:40.446 --> 00:05:41.574
-It is?
-Absolutely.

00:05:41.641 --> 00:05:44.841
So the Walton family's
former offices are above us.

00:05:44.908 --> 00:05:48.590
But now above us is
some co-working for startups.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:52.373
This town has actually organized
incubators and accelerators

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:55.454
where we actually grow startups
from around the United States

00:05:55.521 --> 00:05:56.422
and relocate them.

00:05:56.489 --> 00:05:59.573
So when I shop, I never go to Walmart.

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:01.012
-I'm an Amazon guy.
-Yeah.

00:06:01.508 --> 00:06:03.484
That's the biggest competition, right?

00:06:03.551 --> 00:06:07.660
It is, but what's interesting is Walmart's
really fending them off pretty quickly.

00:06:07.727 --> 00:06:08.610
Come on.

00:06:08.677 --> 00:06:12.479
Walmart's e-commerce growth
has really taken off since COVID.

00:06:12.546 --> 00:06:15.398
Somebody actually goes…
And this is how out of touch I am.

00:06:15.465 --> 00:06:17.685
I know this is
your wheelhouse here, Walmart.

00:06:17.752 --> 00:06:20.888
I would never go to a Walmart website
and order anything.

00:06:20.955 --> 00:06:22.228
That's what Amazon's for.

00:06:22.295 --> 00:06:25.853
Well, it's become very normalized
as you get your groceries

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:28.139
ordered from the app or you schedule it

00:06:28.206 --> 00:06:29.858
and it's brought to you by drone.

00:06:29.925 --> 00:06:31.542
And that R&amp;D is here.

00:06:31.609 --> 00:06:32.675
That bums me out.

00:06:33.110 --> 00:06:34.622
It's happening right above us.

00:06:34.689 --> 00:06:37.186
-Ah, come on. I hate hearing those things.
-Yeah.

00:06:37.253 --> 00:06:39.714
-But they're all buzzing around?
-Yep.

00:06:39.781 --> 00:06:42.670
-We have drone delivery of product here.
-Okay.

00:06:42.737 --> 00:06:45.072
But let's just be devil's advocate on that.

00:06:45.139 --> 00:06:47.801
Convenience, great.
Okay. Efficiency, great.

00:06:47.868 --> 00:06:51.555
Less use and abuse on the roads
and gas being used and all that.

00:06:51.622 --> 00:06:52.519
That's exactly right.

00:06:52.586 --> 00:06:56.097
But do you want to live in a world
where you're out in nature

00:06:56.164 --> 00:06:58.534
and you hear [buzzing] all day long?

00:06:58.601 --> 00:07:00.450
It's a balance. It's a balance.

00:07:00.517 --> 00:07:02.046
You hardly notice it here.

00:07:02.604 --> 00:07:03.868
Okay, I'd love to see it.

00:07:03.935 --> 00:07:06.148
-It's happening right here.

00:07:06.215 --> 00:07:09.146
And it's almost like Jacob's our security.

00:07:09.213 --> 00:07:11.253
-Even though we don't need it.
-We'll cut through here.

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:12.228
Thank you, Jacob.

00:07:12.295 --> 00:07:16.469
The Walton family still owns
nearly half the stock of Walmart.

00:07:16.536 --> 00:07:19.205
There are family offices
is in this building.

00:07:19.272 --> 00:07:21.566
Up here is the office full of startups.

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:25.414
You got all different types
of businesses being built up here.

00:07:25.481 --> 00:07:28.004
All just working in one place,
sharing their ideas.

00:07:28.071 --> 00:07:29.521
It's a really good community.

00:07:29.588 --> 00:07:30.719
Are you into business?

00:07:30.786 --> 00:07:33.266
I'm a finance student at the U of A, so…

00:07:33.333 --> 00:07:35.883
We're gonna hang out
with your buddies later, right?

00:07:35.950 --> 00:07:37.531
Yes, I'm looking forward to it.

00:07:37.598 --> 00:07:39.833
Show me what college life
is like these days.

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:42.295
Fayetteville's a beautiful town.
You'll love it.

00:07:42.362 --> 00:07:44.009
We just walked by a Walmart.

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:46.492
-Where?
-This is a Walmart marketplace.

00:07:46.559 --> 00:07:48.029
Oh, it's a small Walmart.

00:07:48.096 --> 00:07:50.900
Yeah. This is a Walmart marketplace
embedded in downtown.

00:07:50.967 --> 00:07:52.998
-It just blends right in.
-So that's rare.

00:07:53.065 --> 00:07:55.458
You don't see the small Walmarts
in the country.

00:07:55.525 --> 00:07:58.925
Well, Walmart marketplaces are prevalent.
It's just the grocery side.

00:07:58.992 --> 00:08:01.093
But this one here in particular
blends right in.

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:02.993
-But are those rolling out in other places?

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:04.728
-Yes.
-They are? Okay.

00:08:06.686 --> 00:08:09.055
Every one of these doors is a new startup.

00:08:09.122 --> 00:08:10.757
They all work together.

00:08:10.824 --> 00:08:12.837
-How are you guys doing?
-Good.

00:08:12.904 --> 00:08:14.127
What are you working on?

00:08:14.194 --> 00:08:18.442
I do a startup
where we flag risk in addiction relapse

00:08:18.509 --> 00:08:20.038
using biometric wearables.

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:24.302
So we sell into
treatment centers, facilities.

00:08:24.369 --> 00:08:25.252
-Okay.

00:08:25.319 --> 00:08:27.525
-Around substance use disorder.
-That's cool.

00:08:27.592 --> 00:08:33.135
We can identify when people are at risk
of relapse using biometric wearables.

00:08:33.202 --> 00:08:36.894
My little sister has been in and out
of treatment for the last 10 years.

00:08:36.961 --> 00:08:38.793
She can sell ice to Eskimos.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:41.160
And she is so good at
manipulating the system.

00:08:41.227 --> 00:08:44.516
And so by bringing objective data
to the forefront

00:08:44.583 --> 00:08:48.499
of her recovery process,
she can't, like, cheat that.

00:08:48.566 --> 00:08:50.574
-Are you wearing one right now?
-Yeah.

00:08:50.641 --> 00:08:54.300
So this is currently…
You can see this is what people wear.

00:08:54.367 --> 00:08:58.661
I have a PHQ-9 assessment due,
which is a clinically validated assessment.

00:08:59.143 --> 00:09:01.574
Okay.
So why not go to the Bay Area for this?

00:09:01.641 --> 00:09:03.776
There's more venture over there.

00:09:03.843 --> 00:09:05.273
It's not that…

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:08.072
Well, so being here
for health tech is really important

00:09:08.139 --> 00:09:10.652
because we've got
so much going on in health care,

00:09:10.719 --> 00:09:12.248
innovation in health care.

00:09:12.796 --> 00:09:14.750
At the Alice Walton School of Medicine,

00:09:14.817 --> 00:09:18.157
she's redefining
how health care is being done.

00:09:18.224 --> 00:09:20.789
I came in 2018. I liked it.

00:09:20.856 --> 00:09:22.579
At the time, I was living in DC.

00:09:23.043 --> 00:09:24.961
And then post-COVID, I was like,

00:09:25.028 --> 00:09:29.357
I want something smaller town
but big city amenities.

00:09:29.424 --> 00:09:30.533
I want nature.

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:34.549
I want to be able to have everything
within 5 to 15 minute drive.

00:09:34.616 --> 00:09:35.499
-Okay.

00:09:35.566 --> 00:09:37.493
And Bentonville's awesome for that.

00:09:39.974 --> 00:09:41.824
[Peter] So like many American cities,

00:09:41.891 --> 00:09:44.304
you're not dealing with
homelessness in the park.

00:09:44.371 --> 00:09:46.215
No, it's very unusual.

00:09:46.282 --> 00:09:48.130
You guys just don't accept it.

00:09:48.197 --> 00:09:49.726
You're not gonna let that fly.

00:09:49.793 --> 00:09:52.114
It actually hasn't been
like a removal process.

00:09:52.181 --> 00:09:53.873
As a metropolitan area,

00:09:53.940 --> 00:09:58.126
Fayetteville has basically
our metro's homeless population

00:09:58.193 --> 00:10:00.048
'cause that's where the servicing is.

00:10:00.115 --> 00:10:02.449
So homeless shelter, the food,

00:10:02.516 --> 00:10:04.873
that system,
is built out in South Fayetteville.

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:07.209
So far from here, like 30 minutes or so.

00:10:07.276 --> 00:10:08.527
-30 minutes.
-Okay.

00:10:09.175 --> 00:10:11.044
One hour away from the bikes.

00:10:11.111 --> 00:10:12.989
Yeah, we're an hour from the bikes.
Didn't lock them.

00:10:13.056 --> 00:10:15.646
-And I left all my camera stuff in here.
-Yeah.

00:10:15.713 --> 00:10:17.683
-That's what you want.
-No problem.

00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:22.201
[Peter] Toby, the town is connected
with these bike paths, yeah?

00:10:22.268 --> 00:10:24.414
Yes. All of Northwest Arkansas is.

00:10:24.854 --> 00:10:28.094
So that's great.
You're right in downtown, you hop on this.

00:10:28.161 --> 00:10:30.766
It's great in these times
where there's a lot of

00:10:31.396 --> 00:10:34.472
negativity in media,
with our politicians,

00:10:34.539 --> 00:10:36.068
with the world in general.

00:10:36.596 --> 00:10:39.067
And getting in environments like this where

00:10:39.778 --> 00:10:42.258
you can just feel the optimism,

00:10:42.325 --> 00:10:43.751
see the energy.

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:46.746
Bentonville, not long ago, was nothing.

00:10:47.433 --> 00:10:48.727
And now it's thriving.

00:10:49.276 --> 00:10:52.338
You know what I'm saying?
All these towns are in their cycles.

00:10:52.405 --> 00:10:53.299
-That's true.
-Right?

00:10:53.366 --> 00:10:56.623
I was in Pine Bluff not that long ago

00:10:57.134 --> 00:10:58.075
it was thriving.

00:10:58.490 --> 00:11:00.997
It was where it was happening
and this was nothing.

00:11:01.064 --> 00:11:01.947
-Well…
-Right?

00:11:02.014 --> 00:11:04.361
And now this is full steam ahead.

00:11:04.428 --> 00:11:07.590
The whole nation was based on farming
and Pine Bluff was a mecca

00:11:07.657 --> 00:11:09.461
of that rice and cotton system.

00:11:09.527 --> 00:11:13.934
And with the river right there,
the Arkansas River, transport it out.

00:11:14.607 --> 00:11:17.331
These office buildings
just keep on going huh?

00:11:17.398 --> 00:11:21.006
-I work for the University of Arkansas.
That's my office.

00:11:21.814 --> 00:11:24.077
-Okay, so this is it, right?
The headquarters?

00:11:24.144 --> 00:11:27.418
-This is the beginning.
-What's the size of the headquarters?

00:11:27.485 --> 00:11:29.603
There's about 14,000 employees here.

00:11:30.073 --> 00:11:32.063
14,000 employees. How many acres?

00:11:32.975 --> 00:11:34.747
I believe it's about 300 acres.

00:11:34.814 --> 00:11:36.459
-300 acres?
-Yep.

00:11:36.526 --> 00:11:37.442
The whole place?

00:11:38.173 --> 00:11:41.058
So Walmart's headquarters was very humble.

00:11:41.125 --> 00:11:44.537
It was just in a one warehouse
all the way until last year.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:47.403
-Seriously?
-Yeah.

00:11:47.470 --> 00:11:49.379
They went to town on this operation.

00:11:49.446 --> 00:11:52.014
This is about
talent attraction and retention.

00:11:52.081 --> 00:11:55.997
-So you're saying the model here is
get the millennials and the Z's in.

00:11:56.064 --> 00:11:57.064
Yeah, absolutely.

00:11:57.131 --> 00:12:00.039
-You need to make it interesting enough
for them to be here.

00:12:00.106 --> 00:12:02.809
Yeah, they want a balanced lifestyle,
they want food,

00:12:02.876 --> 00:12:05.288
they want live music, they want outdoors,

00:12:05.740 --> 00:12:07.854
and everything here
is about whole health.

00:12:07.921 --> 00:12:10.255
So it's centered on nature,

00:12:10.835 --> 00:12:12.842
Taking breaks during your work day.

00:12:12.909 --> 00:12:17.278
This is right in the middle of campus
and people are walking to coffee shops.

00:12:17.345 --> 00:12:20.296
That's actually a fitness center
just for Walmart employees.

00:12:20.740 --> 00:12:23.412
-Okay, so Toby, when I think of Walmart,

00:12:23.479 --> 00:12:26.273
I'm not thinking of
the healthiest place on the planet.

00:12:26.340 --> 00:12:29.164
I'm thinking bags of chips,
Coca-Cola, and Pepsi.

00:12:29.723 --> 00:12:32.610
Though I will say
they have kombucha now, which is cool.

00:12:32.677 --> 00:12:36.181
Synergy Kombucha.
Which I think is great. I drink that stuff.

00:12:36.623 --> 00:12:39.731
They've gotten better
with the produce, I will say.

00:12:39.798 --> 00:12:41.548
'Cause some of these towns I go to

00:12:41.615 --> 00:12:44.910
the best thing going for groceries
is Walmart, right?

00:12:45.399 --> 00:12:47.805
Often in food deserts,
Walmart's the only option.

00:12:47.872 --> 00:12:49.401
Walmart's the only option.

00:12:49.468 --> 00:12:52.592
But then when I'm out here in Bentonville,

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:56.476
It doesn't have the Walmart feel at all,
I'm gonna say.

00:12:56.998 --> 00:12:58.060
Does that make sense?

00:12:58.127 --> 00:13:01.427
I understand what you're saying,
but here this is the Walmart feel.

00:13:01.494 --> 00:13:03.764
-There are different Walmart universes.

00:13:03.831 --> 00:13:08.006
Yeah. People from all over the world
relocate here to work for Walmart.

00:13:08.073 --> 00:13:10.151
Okay, a lot of Indians, right?

00:13:10.218 --> 00:13:13.885
There's a lot from India, there's a lot
from all across the United States.

00:13:13.952 --> 00:13:16.498
The summer internship program,
for instance,

00:13:16.565 --> 00:13:19.676
there's 50,000 applicants
and they only accept 500.

00:13:20.295 --> 00:13:23.745
And they're from all over the United States
including the Ivy Leagues.

00:13:23.812 --> 00:13:26.328
-Are they hiring right now?
-They're always hiring.

00:13:26.395 --> 00:13:28.747
Look at this stonework here.
That's beautiful.

00:13:28.814 --> 00:13:31.329
I mean, you wish Walmart
could all look like this.

00:13:31.396 --> 00:13:33.576
Economically,
there's no way that would work

00:13:33.643 --> 00:13:37.159
if all the Walmarts around the country
had this look and feel. Right?

00:13:37.226 --> 00:13:40.376
It's too expensive to build,
but this is nice.

00:13:40.443 --> 00:13:43.006
Yeah, this is about
talent attraction and retention,

00:13:43.073 --> 00:13:45.796
but of course the Walmart stores are about

00:13:45.863 --> 00:13:50.241
optimizing for value so you can have
affordable produce and product.

00:13:50.308 --> 00:13:51.191
-Yeah.

00:13:53.146 --> 00:13:54.721
-[man] Sorry.
-Hey, no problem.

00:13:54.788 --> 00:13:57.720
-Hey guys, how's it going here right now?
-Awesome.

00:13:57.787 --> 00:13:59.514
-Do you like working here?
-We do.

00:13:59.581 --> 00:14:00.795
Where are you guys from?

00:14:00.862 --> 00:14:05.026
He's from here. I'm from California.
I travel every few weeks.

00:14:05.093 --> 00:14:08.727
-Oh, okay. So you live in California,
you travel here for work.

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:11.146
-My colleagues, yes.
-It's awesome.

00:14:11.213 --> 00:14:14.131
You should have seen it 16 years back.
It's very different.

00:14:14.198 --> 00:14:16.218
-You've been with the company that long?

00:14:16.285 --> 00:14:19.529
Yeah. Like 6:00,
it would shut down in the evening,

00:14:19.596 --> 00:14:22.358
but now it's like… it's awesome.

00:14:22.425 --> 00:14:23.719
-The whole town?
-Yeah.

00:14:24.803 --> 00:14:26.156
Let's cruise this zone.

00:14:26.852 --> 00:14:29.710
There we go, guys.
We have a full-on food truck scene.

00:14:29.777 --> 00:14:31.306
That is a cool food truck.

00:14:32.177 --> 00:14:34.882
So this campus is open.
Anyone can cruise through here?

00:14:34.949 --> 00:14:36.341
-Open campus, yeah.

00:14:36.408 --> 00:14:39.557
[Peter] It just keeps going and going.
It's like its own city.

00:14:39.624 --> 00:14:40.713
[Toby] It is.

00:14:40.780 --> 00:14:41.835
Never ends.

00:14:41.902 --> 00:14:44.207
-Never ends. That is the truth.

00:14:44.790 --> 00:14:47.247
So it might even be cooler or just as cool

00:14:47.314 --> 00:14:50.573
to work at Walmart
as it is Apple and Google.

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:52.099
That's right. Yeah, actually.

00:14:52.166 --> 00:14:54.416
Are they trying?
That's the competition right?

00:14:54.483 --> 00:14:56.012
It is for talent for sure.

00:14:58.865 --> 00:15:01.581
[Jacob] So even just on
the outskirts of Bentonville,

00:15:01.648 --> 00:15:04.546
a house like this will still go for 800k,

00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:07.506
close to a million,
just because of the location.

00:15:07.573 --> 00:15:10.426
They have the children's center
down there that's massive.

00:15:10.493 --> 00:15:12.669
It's almost like a company town.

00:15:13.217 --> 00:15:16.881
Sort of and all of
the largest investments in the town

00:15:16.948 --> 00:15:18.833
come from one company,

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:22.188
but it's been a net benefit
on everyone that lives here.

00:15:22.255 --> 00:15:25.593
-Yeah, like a company town
seemed to be done the right way.

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:27.510
-I think it's done the right way.

00:15:27.577 --> 00:15:29.308
This is a children's museum.

00:15:29.375 --> 00:15:30.993
-Who's the Scott family?

00:15:31.060 --> 00:15:33.877
-That was a former executive at Walmart.

00:15:34.896 --> 00:15:37.167
-Oh, wow. Look at that.

00:15:37.930 --> 00:15:40.326
This is like something
you'd see in Scandinavia.

00:15:40.393 --> 00:15:43.981
-Yeah. This is the new
Alice L. Walton School of Medicine.

00:15:44.048 --> 00:15:46.506
It's the first in the world MD program

00:15:46.573 --> 00:15:49.584
centered on whole health,
the whole spectrum of whole health.

00:15:49.651 --> 00:15:51.561
-Seriously?
-Mind, body, yes.

00:15:51.628 --> 00:15:55.303
[Peter] What a beautiful building
and you just ride right through it.

00:15:55.370 --> 00:15:56.253
[Toby] You can.

00:15:56.702 --> 00:15:58.725
She's centered on art and wellness.

00:15:58.792 --> 00:16:01.603
And she looks at it as one thing,
art and wellness.

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:05.605
So on her campus is
Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art.

00:16:06.035 --> 00:16:10.279
So you can go to the roof
and there's trees and cactuses above us.

00:16:10.346 --> 00:16:12.668
-Wanna do a quick…
-Yeah. Let's do it.

00:16:13.190 --> 00:16:14.435
Let's park those.

00:16:15.141 --> 00:16:18.445
The inaugural class
just happened in August of 2025.

00:16:18.512 --> 00:16:20.629
So this is a brand new medical school.

00:16:20.696 --> 00:16:22.177
First students just enrolled.

00:16:22.244 --> 00:16:24.245
Yeah. They started in August.

00:16:24.675 --> 00:16:28.287
So the next class,
the second class will start this summer.

00:16:28.354 --> 00:16:29.433
Tuition is free?

00:16:29.500 --> 00:16:32.691
For the first five years,
tuition is free for the first five classes.

00:16:32.758 --> 00:16:35.272
-Bring in the best?
-Bring in the best of the best.

00:16:35.339 --> 00:16:39.464
There are people from Duke University,
Stanford, and Cleveland Clinic.

00:16:39.531 --> 00:16:43.164
They're all involved in kind of
formation of this medical school.

00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:45.490
-And this is the roof?
-That's right.

00:16:45.557 --> 00:16:48.128
It's the largest green roof
in the United States.

00:16:48.195 --> 00:16:49.713
It's two and a half acres.

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:51.366
-You have cacti, prickly pear?

00:16:51.433 --> 00:16:54.110
Yeah. So we're on the roof
of the medical school,

00:16:54.177 --> 00:16:56.237
but on this half is clinics.

00:16:56.304 --> 00:16:59.993
So there'll be clinics on this side,
on that side is the classroom.

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:03.394
The culture here is to
spend time outside during the workday.

00:17:03.461 --> 00:17:06.219
You'll see this even down at
the University of Arkansas.

00:17:06.286 --> 00:17:09.103
There's a mountain bike trail
that goes through campus.

00:17:09.170 --> 00:17:10.683
I so wouldn't go to school.

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:11.633
[Toby chuckles]

00:17:12.347 --> 00:17:14.216
[Peter] Since 2020,

00:17:14.283 --> 00:17:18.050
a 13.8 increase in population
here in this town.

00:17:18.117 --> 00:17:19.533
-Yeah.
-That's insane.

00:17:19.600 --> 00:17:22.973
[Toby] In the year 2000 there was
only 19,000 people in Bentonville.

00:17:23.040 --> 00:17:26.345
-So it's not even just Walmart jobs,
construction jobs galore.

00:17:26.412 --> 00:17:27.631
-Yeah, absolutely.

00:17:27.698 --> 00:17:30.914
-Okay. You guys though,
you got to worry about that a bit.

00:17:30.981 --> 00:17:33.906
You don't want to blow out
what's so nice up here.

00:17:33.973 --> 00:17:36.208
That's where
the mountain biking is up there?

00:17:36.275 --> 00:17:38.153
-Yeah. It's a tricky spot because

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:42.349
outdoor recreation and the great outdoors
in the Ozarks, is our culture.

00:17:42.416 --> 00:17:47.038
This metropolitan area is growing so fast.
We'll pass a million in the next decade.

00:17:47.105 --> 00:17:50.690
So there's very intentionality
about narrowing our footprint,

00:17:50.757 --> 00:17:52.757
having more dense population here.

00:17:53.179 --> 00:17:56.334
So there's actually a coordinated effort
across all these cities

00:17:56.401 --> 00:17:58.083
to actually redo zoning laws.

00:17:58.150 --> 00:18:00.920
So that way you can have
more homes per single family.

00:18:00.987 --> 00:18:03.437
-You're gonna have to build up.
-Have to build up.

00:18:03.504 --> 00:18:07.481
-Do more of that.
-And also do more density, ADUs.

00:18:07.548 --> 00:18:11.136
Go to where you can have
two or three dwellings on one parcel.

00:18:11.637 --> 00:18:14.994
-Okay. So I'm sure it's divisive
depending on who you're talking to.

00:18:15.061 --> 00:18:17.161
Some people, the locals that grew up here,

00:18:17.228 --> 00:18:20.052
I'm sure some are like,
what happened to my town?

00:18:20.536 --> 00:18:24.523
Well, there are unicorns left
where people grew up here,

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:26.744
but almost everybody's from somewhere else.

00:18:26.811 --> 00:18:29.584
But there is a little bit of rage
against the change.

00:18:29.651 --> 00:18:31.617
I mean this is a rapidly changing town.

00:18:31.684 --> 00:18:33.103
That's so rapid.

00:18:33.170 --> 00:18:36.065
-It used to be where people
would migrate to the jobs.

00:18:36.132 --> 00:18:38.133
Now people are migrating to livability.

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.318
Its challenge is affordable housing.

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:45.918
-This is beautiful, isn't it?
-Yeah.

00:18:45.985 --> 00:18:49.638
-It's so amazing.
-Yeah. It's pretty special, isn't it?

00:18:49.705 --> 00:18:53.101
-What's your dog's name?
-That is Saturday.

00:18:53.168 --> 00:18:55.391
-Saturday?
-Yeah.

00:18:55.458 --> 00:18:58.463
We're making a video of Bentonville
'cause it's so beautiful.

00:18:58.530 --> 00:18:59.828
My first time here.

00:18:59.895 --> 00:19:01.493
-I'm Alice.
-Alice.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:03.813
Peter. I live in Florida.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:04.763
Okay.

00:19:04.830 --> 00:19:07.946
But I had no idea
Northwest Arkansas looked like this.

00:19:08.013 --> 00:19:10.818
Most people don't.
It's a pleasant surprise.

00:19:10.885 --> 00:19:13.508
-This architecture is top-notch.
-Oh, thank you.

00:19:13.575 --> 00:19:16.833
I thought I was coming into Finland.
Finland or Scandinavia.

00:19:16.900 --> 00:19:18.209
It is kind of.

00:19:18.276 --> 00:19:20.092
-Take care, ma'am.
-Thank you.

00:19:20.159 --> 00:19:21.100
Have a good one.

00:19:23.092 --> 00:19:23.975
She works here?

00:19:24.790 --> 00:19:27.168
You just met
the wealthiest woman on the planet.

00:19:27.235 --> 00:19:29.165
-That's Alice Walton.
-No way.

00:19:29.232 --> 00:19:31.464
She's worth $130 billion.

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:33.579
-No way.
-Yeah.

00:19:33.646 --> 00:19:35.698
-You didn't stage that?
-Not at all.

00:19:35.765 --> 00:19:38.966
I looked and I was like, guys,
should probably turned over there.

00:19:42.030 --> 00:19:45.563
We'll cut through the woods
and we'll cut over to Crystal Bridges.

00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:47.728
-That's so cool.
-She built all this.

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:51.873
There are a lot of
famous billionaires in the United States.

00:19:51.940 --> 00:19:57.226
But we only have one family
that acts like basically the Vanderbilts,

00:19:57.293 --> 00:19:59.613
having to do with
giving back to a community.

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:03.503
And they center so narrowly
to Northwest Arkansas.

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:06.752
So what you're seeing here
is a massive redevelopment.

00:20:06.819 --> 00:20:10.609
And they want to use Bentonville
as an example for the rest of the world.

00:20:10.676 --> 00:20:13.565
-Okay, the money is coming back into here,

00:20:14.133 --> 00:20:17.954
but it's not like Carnegie where you saw
the libraries all over the country

00:20:18.021 --> 00:20:19.093
in every small town.

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:22.310
The Gilded Age wealth that was
going out throughout the country.

00:20:22.377 --> 00:20:25.552
-I can't speak for the family
but it's very intentional

00:20:25.619 --> 00:20:27.240
to make Northwest Arkansas

00:20:27.307 --> 00:20:30.182
the greatest place to
live, work, and play in the United States.

00:20:30.249 --> 00:20:31.949
And of course, that's self-serving

00:20:32.016 --> 00:20:35.717
because they can attract talent here
to work for corporate here.

00:20:37.390 --> 00:20:39.906
All right, guys, gotta say,
this is a new for me,

00:20:39.973 --> 00:20:43.601
quite a fascinating experience.

00:20:43.668 --> 00:20:45.729
I hope it comes through the camera

00:20:45.796 --> 00:20:48.358
because it just goes to show

00:20:48.896 --> 00:20:52.238
you can travel the country
full-time for a job

00:20:53.083 --> 00:20:57.183
and constantly come into things
you never knew existed.

00:20:57.250 --> 00:21:01.446
I mean, I've heard of Bentonville,
but I never thought anything of it.

00:21:01.513 --> 00:21:06.113
That's the beauty of living in
such a large, dynamic country.

00:21:06.180 --> 00:21:09.360
Is there are millions
of different worlds to enter.

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:13.793
This is the Heartland
Whole Health Institute.

00:21:13.865 --> 00:21:16.963
It's another branch of
Alice Walton's efforts.

00:21:17.030 --> 00:21:18.562
Two things are happening here.

00:21:18.629 --> 00:21:23.856
There's a team focused on trying to change
how healthcare is done in America.

00:21:23.923 --> 00:21:29.083
And the other thing is the Walton family
is incubating a new STEM university

00:21:29.150 --> 00:21:31.815
that will begin in 2029
here in Bentonville.

00:21:32.440 --> 00:21:35.605
The founding team's in there
working on the future of education.

00:21:35.672 --> 00:21:38.959
Experiential learning,
industry collaborations, learning by doing.

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:42.383
-How old is this building?
-It's about two years old.

00:21:42.856 --> 00:21:45.103
There is an art gallery on the first floor.

00:21:45.170 --> 00:21:47.111
[Peter] What a stunning building.

00:21:47.630 --> 00:21:50.256
[Toby] The flagstone is
quintessential Arkansas.

00:21:50.323 --> 00:21:51.783
-Do you know the architect?

00:21:51.850 --> 00:21:54.253
-Marlon Blackwell is the architect.

00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:58.343
Wow, guys. I really hope
the camera captures some of this.

00:21:58.410 --> 00:22:01.681
Had no clue we'd be doing
an architectural tour today.

00:22:04.626 --> 00:22:06.136
What's the name of this place?

00:22:06.203 --> 00:22:09.384
-Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art.

00:22:09.970 --> 00:22:12.116
-In this small city?
-Mm-hmm.

00:22:12.183 --> 00:22:16.083
Alice procured the best art
across the Americas and brought 'em here.

00:22:16.150 --> 00:22:20.993
She quietly did it for about a decade
and then they opened this in 2011.

00:22:21.060 --> 00:22:23.726
-So she just had this grand vision
of what to do here?

00:22:23.793 --> 00:22:24.676
-Yep.

00:22:26.454 --> 00:22:30.154
[Toby] This is the largest collection
of American art in the United States.

00:22:30.221 --> 00:22:32.578
It goes from pre-colonial 1600s
to modern times.

00:22:32.645 --> 00:22:34.259
Native American art as well.

00:22:35.810 --> 00:22:39.663
The Leonardo DiCaprio movie
is based on this famous painting.

00:22:39.730 --> 00:22:41.194
-The Revenant.
-Yep.

00:22:41.261 --> 00:22:44.035
And when he filmed a movie in Tulsa

00:22:44.102 --> 00:22:46.802
which is only two hours,
he came to visit the painting.

00:22:46.869 --> 00:22:47.752
-No way.
-Yeah.

00:22:47.819 --> 00:22:50.818
-That's my favorite director,
Alejandro Inarritu.

00:22:50.885 --> 00:22:51.813
-Yep. That's right.

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:54.868
Babel, 21 Grams, Beautiful.

00:22:54.935 --> 00:22:55.818
Yeah.

00:22:55.885 --> 00:22:58.457
-Birdman. Birdman was a classic.
-Yeah.

00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:00.339
One of my favorites.

00:23:02.060 --> 00:23:03.060
Georgia O'Keeffe.

00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:07.641
[Toby] This is Brooklyn in 1820.

00:23:07.708 --> 00:23:11.038
You actually can look up
this exact intersection that still exists.

00:23:11.105 --> 00:23:13.951
It's actually right underneath
the Brooklyn Bridge now.

00:23:14.550 --> 00:23:15.668
[diners chattering]

00:23:21.924 --> 00:23:24.293
-What is this place?
-This is called the castle.

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:26.007
Looks like a castle up here.

00:23:26.546 --> 00:23:29.506
Everyone can send it from here.
You work your way to the top.

00:23:29.573 --> 00:23:31.282
From here there's three ways down.

00:23:31.349 --> 00:23:34.783
You got some black diamond,
blue stuff, and some green stuff.

00:23:34.850 --> 00:23:36.263
-Sweet.
-Yeah.

00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:37.809
This guy's gonna send it.

00:23:37.876 --> 00:23:39.523
-Here he goes.
-Let's see it.

00:23:42.740 --> 00:23:44.975
Are we gonna see it through the trees?

00:23:49.220 --> 00:23:52.053
[Peter] Oh, this is sweet.
Roller coaster stuff.

00:23:52.446 --> 00:23:55.705
For any mountain bikers out there,
this is what you want to see.

00:23:55.772 --> 00:23:56.823
Look at that.

00:23:56.890 --> 00:24:00.065
-You can go as extreme as you want.
-Absolutely.

00:24:00.132 --> 00:24:02.582
-There's some big drops?
-There is some big drops.

00:24:02.649 --> 00:24:04.429
[Peter] Right off the highway here.

00:24:04.496 --> 00:24:06.956
And then it goes all down this way.

00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:16.034
We're gonna hit the road soon.
You're gonna take off, right?

00:24:16.101 --> 00:24:18.003
-I am. Yep.
-Toby's taking off.

00:24:18.070 --> 00:24:19.643
Jacob's taking over.

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:21.503
But Toby, what was this before?

00:24:21.570 --> 00:24:23.536
This was a Kraft cheese factory.

00:24:23.603 --> 00:24:26.783
Now it's a modern art gallery
with a cocktail lounge on top.

00:24:26.850 --> 00:24:30.093
-I love when they take old factories
and do this, you know?

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:34.116
Okay, Toby, before you depart,
here's my big question.

00:24:34.183 --> 00:24:38.323
I get it. It's not just a one-horse show,
whatever you want to call it.

00:24:38.390 --> 00:24:40.023
There's more than Walmart.

00:24:40.090 --> 00:24:41.619
But say Walmart went down.

00:24:42.311 --> 00:24:44.373
Doesn't look like it at all, obviously.

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:45.985
But say, whatever.

00:24:46.052 --> 00:24:48.189
Amazon, a new player comes on board.

00:24:48.256 --> 00:24:49.734
Walmart has tough times.

00:24:50.340 --> 00:24:53.163
The whole town's going
down with it, though, right?

00:24:53.230 --> 00:24:54.701
Walmart's very resilient.

00:24:55.212 --> 00:24:59.073
Actually, when there's recessions,
Walmart actually outperforms everything.

00:24:59.140 --> 00:25:00.809
So this is very resilient.

00:25:00.876 --> 00:25:03.036
We actually have
a really strong backbone here.

00:25:03.103 --> 00:25:06.567
But there's innovators moving in here
by the day and they're the ones

00:25:06.634 --> 00:25:10.399
that are gonna be part of
the next chapter of Northwest Arkansas.

00:25:10.960 --> 00:25:11.878
[jazz music]

00:25:22.495 --> 00:25:24.113
So this is the Walmart Amp.

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:26.770
It was opened in I think around 2012.

00:25:26.837 --> 00:25:30.300
Huge shows, probably 10,000 people,
anyone that you can think of.

00:25:30.367 --> 00:25:32.924
We got Dave Matthews this year,
Mumford &amp; Sons.

00:25:32.991 --> 00:25:34.962
-I've been to tons of shows here.
-Nice.

00:25:35.029 --> 00:25:38.049
-We're out of Bentonville, right?
-We're in Rogers, Arkansas.

00:25:38.116 --> 00:25:39.886
-Okay, totally different town?
-Yes.

00:25:39.953 --> 00:25:42.983
This is where all of
the corporate vendors are setting up.

00:25:43.050 --> 00:25:45.702
So right in front of us,
you'll see all the high rises

00:25:45.769 --> 00:25:49.938
from General Mills, Coke, Colgate, Nestle.
They're all right here.

00:25:50.005 --> 00:25:53.776
Because their biggest client is Walmart,
they keep a presence really close.

00:25:53.843 --> 00:25:56.966
And they've built out this area
just in the past 10 years.

00:25:57.033 --> 00:25:58.654
None of this was here.

00:25:58.721 --> 00:26:01.621
-10 years ago, nothing was here?
-None of these high rises.

00:26:01.688 --> 00:26:04.146
The Walmart Amp was just put in.
This is very new.

00:26:04.213 --> 00:26:06.323
I think it's been sustainable so far,

00:26:06.390 --> 00:26:10.163
and we're still projected
to keep growing the next few years.

00:26:10.230 --> 00:26:12.304
But it's definitely happened really fast.

00:26:12.371 --> 00:26:15.025
So kind of hard to contemplate
what's going on…

00:26:15.092 --> 00:26:16.386
-…in this area.
-Right.

00:26:16.860 --> 00:26:18.341
And all of this just pops up.

00:26:18.408 --> 00:26:22.100
So even us locals
 are still exploring all the new stuff.

00:26:22.167 --> 00:26:24.187
Okay.
Has there been a huge displacement,

00:26:24.254 --> 00:26:27.195
or there just weren't
that many people here before?

00:26:27.703 --> 00:26:29.503
I think there's some displacement.

00:26:29.570 --> 00:26:33.141
The properties around here
have gotten significantly more expensive.

00:26:33.208 --> 00:26:35.760
I read an article that
this neighborhood we're going to,

00:26:35.827 --> 00:26:40.466
the average home price
10 years ago exactly was $800,000.

00:26:41.120 --> 00:26:43.471
And just looking at Zillow
the last few days

00:26:43.538 --> 00:26:45.530
the average is $1.5 to $2 million.

00:26:45.597 --> 00:26:47.566
-Where we're going right now?
-Where we're going right now.

00:26:47.633 --> 00:26:50.370
And you're getting us into arguably

00:26:50.437 --> 00:26:53.223
the nicest neighborhood in the whole area.

00:26:53.290 --> 00:26:55.435
Arguably all of Northwest Arkansas.

00:26:55.502 --> 00:26:58.266
-It's the nicest one I've seen.
-And we got gate access?

00:26:58.333 --> 00:26:59.258
We do.

00:26:59.325 --> 00:27:01.892
-And you got a connection?
-We're gonna talk to Jim.

00:27:01.972 --> 00:27:02.986
-Jim.
-Very cool guy.

00:27:03.053 --> 00:27:06.313
-Jim's got stories?
-You'll love him. He's got stories.

00:27:06.877 --> 00:27:09.832
-All right. We're in, guys.
-What's this place called again?

00:27:09.899 --> 00:27:11.683
Pinnacle Hills Country Club.

00:27:11.750 --> 00:27:15.103
They start getting much bigger
there near the golf course.

00:27:15.650 --> 00:27:19.230
[Jacob] Kind of a Tuscan style.
Beautiful back here.

00:27:19.755 --> 00:27:22.840
-So this is all Walmart money pretty much?

00:27:22.907 --> 00:27:23.853
-A lot of it.

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:26.569
-Walmart related money.
-Walmart vendors.

00:27:26.636 --> 00:27:27.754
There's the course.

00:27:29.030 --> 00:27:32.830
-So you're saying these are $1.82 million?
They got to be more than that.

00:27:32.897 --> 00:27:34.916
Oh, some of them are closer to four.

00:27:35.381 --> 00:27:36.932
-What's your connection to Jim?

00:27:36.999 --> 00:27:41.072
I met Jim at that startup office
that we went to earlier.

00:27:41.459 --> 00:27:43.463
He's a great guy. He's easy to like.

00:27:43.530 --> 00:27:46.121
Told him about how
I was studying at the U of A.

00:27:46.188 --> 00:27:47.766
Interested in entrepreneurship.

00:27:47.833 --> 00:27:49.556
He said he's always happy to help.

00:27:49.623 --> 00:27:53.105
So he's just a good mentor for people
around here and he's done a lot.

00:27:53.172 --> 00:27:55.173
-What did he do? What was his business?

00:27:55.240 --> 00:27:58.153
So he's invested in a variety of things.

00:27:58.220 --> 00:28:00.589
One of his biggest projects
was Good Day Farms,

00:28:00.656 --> 00:28:01.968
which is a big dispensary.

00:28:02.035 --> 00:28:03.453
-Weed dispensary?
-Yeah.

00:28:03.520 --> 00:28:05.403
Spread across several states.

00:28:05.470 --> 00:28:08.712
You'll have to ask him
what his early start was.

00:28:08.779 --> 00:28:11.727
But he's in law
and he has his own law firm here.

00:28:16.310 --> 00:28:18.839
[Jim] Welcome to Arkansas!
Have you been here long?

00:28:18.906 --> 00:28:19.966
A couple of days.

00:28:20.033 --> 00:28:22.454
Nice to meet you.
Thanks for meeting up with us.

00:28:22.521 --> 00:28:23.442
Yeah, absolutely.

00:28:23.509 --> 00:28:26.578
We bought this house a couple months ago,
so we're working on…

00:28:26.645 --> 00:28:29.797
We've got new windows coming in,
so it's a little beat up.

00:28:29.865 --> 00:28:30.833
-It's beautiful.

00:28:30.900 --> 00:28:33.489
Great. Let's put the mic on you,
if you don't mind.

00:28:33.562 --> 00:28:35.388
-Jacob's out. Jim's in.
-Okay.

00:28:36.023 --> 00:28:37.718
-How do we do that?
-Like that

00:28:37.785 --> 00:28:39.293
-How you been?
-Wonderful.

00:28:39.360 --> 00:28:41.753
Good to see you, man.
You been out here before?

00:28:41.820 --> 00:28:45.349
You been out for doing some things
the last couple of days?

00:28:45.416 --> 00:28:47.330
We've been cruising Bentonville today.

00:28:47.397 --> 00:28:48.979
-Oh, good.
-It's a first for me.

00:28:49.046 --> 00:28:52.586
Oh, good. Good deal. They said that
he tried to get you to come down.

00:28:52.653 --> 00:28:55.168
-Shoes off?
-No, you're fine. Don't worry about it.

00:28:55.235 --> 00:28:57.258
-You just moved in here?
-We sure did.

00:28:57.325 --> 00:29:00.353
And the funny thing is
we bought this from Rob Walton.

00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:02.763
-Sam's son.
-Yeah, he's his oldest son.

00:29:02.830 --> 00:29:04.525
[Peter] Okay. Fantastic.

00:29:04.592 --> 00:29:06.254
It's a really entertaining house.

00:29:06.321 --> 00:29:10.101
Our kids are grown. We're empty nesters,
so we wanted a house where we could

00:29:10.168 --> 00:29:12.300
entertain and have people out here.

00:29:12.367 --> 00:29:14.549
And so this is kind of the guest area.

00:29:14.616 --> 00:29:18.030
This is our bedroom and all that.

00:29:18.097 --> 00:29:22.815
And this is an exercise area that
we're kind of converting into

00:29:22.882 --> 00:29:27.163
a wellness room for compression
and all that kind of stuff.

00:29:27.230 --> 00:29:28.549
-It's the hall of mirrors.

00:29:28.616 --> 00:29:30.634
-That's right.
-Yeah.

00:29:30.701 --> 00:29:32.823
-A little fun house vibe in there.
-Uh-huh.

00:29:32.890 --> 00:29:34.714
And then this is the main bath.

00:29:35.397 --> 00:29:36.663
This is our bathroom.

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:41.329
Got a closet in here
that my wife is real happy with.

00:29:41.396 --> 00:29:44.097
-Oh, that's what you need to do.
Yeah. She's loving it.

00:29:44.164 --> 00:29:47.437
So she's real happy to have a place

00:29:47.504 --> 00:29:49.871
to lay out all the clothes and things.

00:29:49.938 --> 00:29:53.531
So is this the final home, Jim?
Is this the one you were striving for?

00:29:53.598 --> 00:29:57.483
I think I'll go feet first out on this one.
Yeah, this'll do it for me.

00:29:57.550 --> 00:30:01.077
This is kind of,
we call it the library room.

00:30:01.144 --> 00:30:03.371
But I smoke some cigars and stuff.

00:30:03.438 --> 00:30:06.553
So we've got cigars and things in here.

00:30:06.620 --> 00:30:09.600
We're three minutes
up the street is our office.

00:30:09.667 --> 00:30:12.660
We're in Miss Hunt's tower.
Have a real easy commute.

00:30:13.153 --> 00:30:16.803
But this is as you can tell,
I like fireplaces and things like that.

00:30:16.870 --> 00:30:19.173
Just a little area upstairs here

00:30:19.831 --> 00:30:21.890
that, where we like to hang out.

00:30:21.958 --> 00:30:24.806
-When we've got friends over.
-Cool little cove there.

00:30:24.873 --> 00:30:26.116
Yeah. Yep.

00:30:27.193 --> 00:30:28.175
And then this is…

00:30:28.962 --> 00:30:31.222
-Yeah, this is our…
-This is the hangout room?

00:30:31.289 --> 00:30:34.583
This is where we hang out.
And as Jacob knows, I like music and

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:37.334
got my record player
and all this stuff out here.

00:30:37.401 --> 00:30:39.432
And we come out here and listen to music.

00:30:39.499 --> 00:30:42.050
We'll have a listen up out here sometimes.

00:30:42.117 --> 00:30:43.921
-You putting your dance on here?

00:30:43.988 --> 00:30:48.032
We've got four chairs
we've got to put together this weekend.

00:30:48.099 --> 00:30:50.198
We were gonna make it a speakeasy,

00:30:50.265 --> 00:30:53.442
but decided to just keep it the way it is.

00:30:53.509 --> 00:30:55.873
-I like it.
-I tried. Yeah.

00:30:55.940 --> 00:30:59.173
You know, we watched March Madness
and everything up here.

00:30:59.240 --> 00:31:03.783
-Okay. So this part of the state, actually
the state in general is the first for me.

00:31:03.850 --> 00:31:05.882
Northwestern Arkansas. Heard of it.

00:31:05.949 --> 00:31:09.809
Yeah, we're up on the hill,
up on the top of the Ozark mountains.

00:31:09.876 --> 00:31:11.687
-Knew that Walmart was here,

00:31:11.754 --> 00:31:15.260
but had no understanding
that it was this opulent

00:31:15.327 --> 00:31:17.111
and so much going on.

00:31:17.178 --> 00:31:19.199
So much entrepreneurial energy.

00:31:19.266 --> 00:31:21.367
It's really doing really great and it has…

00:31:21.434 --> 00:31:25.151
And that's part of the Waltons,
and Tysons, and Hunts, and all of them.

00:31:25.218 --> 00:31:28.374
They were so far from central Arkansas

00:31:28.441 --> 00:31:32.386
that the legislature,
the politics, and all that is down there.

00:31:32.453 --> 00:31:35.350
And so back in the day,
it was really hard to get up here.

00:31:35.417 --> 00:31:38.097
You didn't have interstate,
you didn't have highways.

00:31:38.164 --> 00:31:42.329
And so those guys all got together
and built up their companies

00:31:42.396 --> 00:31:45.402
And so I think that's a big part.

00:31:45.469 --> 00:31:49.326
-So they, they were remote enough where
they didn't have as much interference.

00:31:49.393 --> 00:31:52.329
Well, they didn't have
as much interference,

00:31:52.396 --> 00:31:55.012
but they also didn't probably have
as much support,

00:31:55.079 --> 00:31:58.922
as you would have from when
you're trying to get funding and things.

00:31:58.989 --> 00:32:01.957
And so they are more for-profit,
more entrepreneurial,

00:32:02.024 --> 00:32:04.723
and I think they just
all got together and said,

00:32:04.790 --> 00:32:07.443
we're gonna build something here
and they really did.

00:32:07.510 --> 00:32:10.949
-Oh, there you go.
-But we have kind of an English garden.

00:32:11.016 --> 00:32:15.551
It's private, you know, to be so close to
all the hustle and bustle of downtown

00:32:15.618 --> 00:32:18.693
northwest Arkansas,
which is how I look at Pinnacle Hills.

00:32:18.760 --> 00:32:21.153
And then you come here,
it's really relaxing.

00:32:21.220 --> 00:32:23.732
-So you've lived here
for a long time, right?

00:32:23.799 --> 00:32:26.568
-Yeah, I've lived in
northwest Arkansas for 26 years.

00:32:26.635 --> 00:32:28.741
-You've done well with business.
-Uh-huh.

00:32:28.808 --> 00:32:31.389
Is it just smooth sailing
in this part of the state?

00:32:31.456 --> 00:32:34.807
Like, you guys aren't really
thinking about the rest of the country,

00:32:34.874 --> 00:32:36.724
or you're sort of in your own bubble?

00:32:36.803 --> 00:32:40.799
I think we're a part of the state
that's more Midwestern than Southern.

00:32:40.866 --> 00:32:45.999
Because we have so many people that have
moved up here to work various things.

00:32:46.066 --> 00:32:50.487
And the heritage that
you typically see in a Southern state is…

00:32:50.554 --> 00:32:53.428
You have first, second,
third generation money up here.

00:32:53.495 --> 00:32:57.942
And in other parts of the state,
you have hundreds of years, you know, of…

00:32:58.009 --> 00:33:01.045
-Like Little Rock has that old money.
-That's right.

00:33:01.112 --> 00:33:03.721
-Here doesn't have that old money?
-I mean, no.

00:33:03.788 --> 00:33:06.590
When you look at Miss Hunt,
she's first generation.

00:33:06.657 --> 00:33:10.173
And then you look at the Waltons,
and they're second and third.

00:33:10.240 --> 00:33:11.973
And Tyson is third.

00:33:12.383 --> 00:33:15.058
It is really hard
for you not to succeed here

00:33:15.125 --> 00:33:18.821
if you want to come here and succeed
and you've got the right mindset

00:33:18.888 --> 00:33:23.253
on where your place should be,
where you want to fit in.

00:33:23.320 --> 00:33:26.153
You've got to want it
more than somebody else.

00:33:26.220 --> 00:33:30.443
Somebody can't want you to succeed
more than you.

00:33:30.932 --> 00:33:32.574
You've got to want to do it.

00:33:32.641 --> 00:33:34.836
You may be really disadvantaged.

00:33:35.305 --> 00:33:39.822
And for some people it's not in the cards,
and for others it is.

00:33:39.889 --> 00:33:43.063
And I don't know
what really separates that.

00:33:43.130 --> 00:33:44.712
-Did you come from money or no?

00:33:44.779 --> 00:33:46.416
No. Not at all.

00:33:46.483 --> 00:33:48.582
I mean, I came from rural Arkansas.

00:33:48.649 --> 00:33:53.111
I was in a town that had a nuclear plant,
so we had engineers and things.

00:33:53.190 --> 00:33:56.317
But my family had a very small
Ace Hardware…

00:33:56.384 --> 00:33:58.603
Well it was Orgill Brothers Hardware store.

00:33:58.670 --> 00:34:00.709
Local hardware store back then.

00:34:01.237 --> 00:34:04.611
And people asked me did you know
you always wanted to be a lawyer?

00:34:04.678 --> 00:34:07.033
And I said I just knew
I didn't want to sell hardware.

00:34:07.100 --> 00:34:10.603
Then I went to school,
went to law school, became a CPA.

00:34:10.670 --> 00:34:13.076
I was working with
the biggest firm in the state.

00:34:13.143 --> 00:34:15.474
In about 1998, they said, hey, we need…

00:34:15.541 --> 00:34:20.515
It's funny, 'cause they said we need to
open up an office in northwest Arkansas.

00:34:20.582 --> 00:34:22.979
And said, we think that the heyday of it,

00:34:23.046 --> 00:34:26.476
the real boom of it has already happened,

00:34:26.848 --> 00:34:29.956
but we think it's gonna be
a nice, stable place to be.

00:34:30.023 --> 00:34:32.499
-'Course, this was almost 30 years ago.
-Okay.

00:34:32.566 --> 00:34:35.216
Had no idea. And the world just took off.

00:34:35.716 --> 00:34:37.154
And so I said I don't know.

00:34:37.221 --> 00:34:40.601
I do mergers and acquisitions
in private equity and venture capital,

00:34:40.668 --> 00:34:44.291
and my wife does family office
and estate planning and things like that.

00:34:44.358 --> 00:34:49.559
And so I said, I don't know that
there's enough deal work to do up there.

00:34:49.626 --> 00:34:51.696
They said, well, go up there and look.

00:34:52.170 --> 00:34:53.961
So it was the fall of 1999.

00:34:54.028 --> 00:34:55.601
I came down here one weekend.

00:34:55.668 --> 00:34:59.350
We were playing Tennessee in football,
and we beat them at the very end.

00:34:59.417 --> 00:35:02.523
And we tore the goalpost down,
took them down to Dixon Street.

00:35:02.590 --> 00:35:05.899
And I said, this is kind of cool.
This'll probably be okay.

00:35:05.966 --> 00:35:08.293
And so I moved up here in August of 2000.

00:35:08.360 --> 00:35:10.493
In 2011, started our own gig.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:13.521
Venture capital and private equity
and those sorts of things

00:35:13.588 --> 00:35:15.876
really started having more of a play,

00:35:15.943 --> 00:35:19.049
more involvement about 2015, 2017, 2018.

00:35:19.116 --> 00:35:23.263
Nothing like it is now and nothing like
you're gonna see 10 years from now.

00:35:23.330 --> 00:35:25.604
-You're optimistic?
-I'm extremely optimistic.

00:35:25.671 --> 00:35:29.000
I don't think there's any place in America,

00:35:29.067 --> 00:35:33.019
to be candid with you, that is like we are.

00:35:33.086 --> 00:35:36.595
I mean, I've been
an ardent student of Silicon Valley

00:35:36.662 --> 00:35:40.070
and deals my whole life.

00:35:40.137 --> 00:35:44.570
And I tell people, I think as trite
or as silly as it may say,

00:35:44.637 --> 00:35:48.833
I feel like we're about at the Atari stage
of Silicon Valley, you know.

00:35:48.900 --> 00:35:51.488
-But I mean,
the majority of venture is there.

00:35:52.249 --> 00:35:54.243
-Currently.
-It is, yeah.

00:35:54.310 --> 00:35:56.294
-And it's almost an ideology.
-Yeah.

00:35:56.361 --> 00:35:58.690
How would you bridge that over to here?

00:35:58.757 --> 00:36:00.330
Because up there you had,

00:36:00.397 --> 00:36:04.910
it all started with Fairchild Semiconductor
and the semiconductor industry and space.

00:36:04.977 --> 00:36:06.857
And it goes into data and

00:36:08.453 --> 00:36:10.672
SAS and all that technology.

00:36:10.739 --> 00:36:13.642
And here you have retail tech

00:36:14.304 --> 00:36:19.412
and becoming health tech and becoming CPG
and logistics and supply chain.

00:36:19.830 --> 00:36:24.334
Downtown Bentonville
kinda feels a bit like that Palo Alto feel

00:36:24.401 --> 00:36:27.263
about in between all that sort of stuff

00:36:27.330 --> 00:36:30.913
and the people that are there today
are making a lot of difference.

00:36:30.980 --> 00:36:34.688
If you study entrepreneurs,
if you understand what people go through

00:36:34.755 --> 00:36:37.795
and what people deal with
and the struggles.

00:36:37.862 --> 00:36:40.353
And these people are famous. You know.

00:36:40.420 --> 00:36:44.525
Jim Walton or Alice or Stuart or Tom
or any of those family members are out,

00:36:45.055 --> 00:36:48.240
not only engaging in the city,
and growing the city,

00:36:48.307 --> 00:36:49.660
but being a part of it.

00:36:50.165 --> 00:36:51.663
You know, that's inspiring.

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:54.788
-Where do you think we're going?
Let's just say the country.

00:36:54.855 --> 00:36:56.880
There's a lot of doom and gloom,
like with AI,

00:36:56.947 --> 00:36:59.687
young people can't find work,
that sort of thing.

00:36:59.754 --> 00:37:01.659
Do you feel like that's the case here or?

00:37:01.726 --> 00:37:03.163
Well, I think we're resilient.

00:37:03.230 --> 00:37:04.951
I think people are resilient.

00:37:05.018 --> 00:37:08.403
And I think people figure out
how to do things.

00:37:08.470 --> 00:37:12.188
What was unfortunate, in my opinion,

00:37:12.255 --> 00:37:15.448
of course, I'm a kid of the '70s and '80s.

00:37:15.508 --> 00:37:17.612
The issue that I got out of COVID

00:37:18.012 --> 00:37:20.174
is that when everybody went remote,

00:37:20.241 --> 00:37:22.955
you know, we're humans,
and when everybody went remote,

00:37:23.022 --> 00:37:26.812
I had a son in college
and a son in high school at that time.

00:37:26.879 --> 00:37:29.864
And that was a difficult challenging time

00:37:30.751 --> 00:37:34.019
to go into something that nobody
had ever really been in before.

00:37:34.453 --> 00:37:37.623
There was an opportunity to get
a lot of government support

00:37:37.690 --> 00:37:41.180
that never existed before
and probably won't ever exist again.

00:37:41.247 --> 00:37:44.235
And once you get that kind of injection,

00:37:44.667 --> 00:37:49.052
it kind of becomes how challenging
is it to get back in the office,

00:37:49.119 --> 00:37:50.798
or get back in the factory,

00:37:50.865 --> 00:37:54.253
get back in the facility
and get back to work?

00:37:54.320 --> 00:37:56.494
You're still trying to figure yourself out.

00:37:56.561 --> 00:38:00.229
And how much of that
was really reality for the long term

00:38:00.671 --> 00:38:03.161
versus, you know, I'm a capitalist.

00:38:03.228 --> 00:38:04.914
I mean, I think I am.

00:38:04.981 --> 00:38:07.143
I mean, I think people… I like to work.

00:38:07.607 --> 00:38:10.126
You know, I like to be engaged,

00:38:10.679 --> 00:38:12.914
and I like to kind of make my own way.

00:38:13.567 --> 00:38:14.989
I think everybody

00:38:15.909 --> 00:38:20.532
most all day every day has something
subliminal in the back of their head

00:38:20.980 --> 00:38:24.510
of a certain degree of uncertainty
that there's just so much

00:38:24.577 --> 00:38:28.017
weirdness going on in the world right now

00:38:28.084 --> 00:38:32.237
that it is on everybody's mind
at some degree.

00:38:32.304 --> 00:38:34.503
And I think it affects everything you do.

00:38:34.570 --> 00:38:37.866
I don't think most people
sit around and stew about it

00:38:37.933 --> 00:38:42.778
as much as they sit around
and kind of wonder, when is this gonna end?

00:38:42.845 --> 00:38:46.019
Whatever "it" is, when is "it" gonna end?

00:38:46.493 --> 00:38:48.875
And I don't know
that anybody really knows what…

00:38:48.942 --> 00:38:53.206
When is the war gonna end?
When is interest rate gonna go down?

00:38:53.273 --> 00:38:55.589
All these all these
different sorts of things.

00:38:55.656 --> 00:38:58.654
When are issues of Washington
gonna calm down?

00:38:58.721 --> 00:39:01.048
Or, you know, a lot of us are gonna say,

00:39:01.424 --> 00:39:03.616
when's it gonna get normal again?

00:39:03.683 --> 00:39:07.742
-The real question is what is normal?
-Yeah. When did it get abnormal?

00:39:08.568 --> 00:39:10.922
Hmm. When did it get abnormal?

00:39:11.470 --> 00:39:14.845
It's kind of like the book 1984.

00:39:14.912 --> 00:39:17.521
When you read 1984
in high school in the '80s

00:39:18.175 --> 00:39:20.934
and you go like,
wow, Big Brother's watching.

00:39:21.001 --> 00:39:23.886
It's like, wow, 
how is that ever gonna happen?

00:39:24.407 --> 00:39:28.570
And then most of that, for all practical
purposes probably exists today,

00:39:28.637 --> 00:39:30.392
but it didn't happen overnight.

00:39:30.459 --> 00:39:35.363
It happened over three, four, five,
ten decades, however long it took.

00:39:35.430 --> 00:39:39.920
Most kids have a certain optimism
on how life is gonna be.

00:39:40.539 --> 00:39:42.843
And then you become an adult
and you gotta work

00:39:42.910 --> 00:39:46.168
and you gotta support yourself
and you gotta support your family

00:39:46.235 --> 00:39:48.203
and you've got to do all these things.

00:39:48.276 --> 00:39:49.746
I think most of us would say,

00:39:49.813 --> 00:39:52.851
if I'd have known it was
gonna be this hard to be an adult,

00:39:52.918 --> 00:39:55.846
I probably would have
played a lot harder when I was a kid.

00:39:55.913 --> 00:39:57.148
You know what I mean?

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:03.811
[Peter] Yeah, Jim made a great point
about when's it gonna get back to normal?

00:40:03.878 --> 00:40:06.581
Like everyone sort of feels like
something's a bit off.

00:40:06.648 --> 00:40:08.006
-Yeah.
-Do you feel that?

00:40:08.546 --> 00:40:11.959
I think we do feel that.
I think my generation feels that.

00:40:12.026 --> 00:40:15.004
And every day we get on social media
and we scroll for hours

00:40:15.071 --> 00:40:18.314
and a lot of it is news
that is not positive news.

00:40:18.381 --> 00:40:21.731
And you kind of just get
this gloomy feel on life

00:40:21.798 --> 00:40:24.286
and you see it every day.
It's just reinforced.

00:40:24.353 --> 00:40:27.632
But I'd love to have the world
kind of break out of that

00:40:27.699 --> 00:40:31.661
and meet up again
and just kind of everyone get along.

00:40:32.141 --> 00:40:34.399
I'm kind of sick of the divisive rhetoric.

00:40:34.902 --> 00:40:36.859
You can blame a lot of it on the media.

00:40:36.926 --> 00:40:39.386
And different sources that we get it from,

00:40:39.453 --> 00:40:42.434
and I think all of us
are way more in common than you think.

00:40:42.501 --> 00:40:43.473
Oh, for sure.

00:40:43.540 --> 00:40:46.208
And that's important
to keep in mind in today's world.

00:40:46.275 --> 00:40:49.137
So most of your generation,
I don't talk to too many of you guys.

00:40:49.204 --> 00:40:51.509
That's why I was excited
when you reached out.

00:40:51.576 --> 00:40:52.459
Of course.

00:40:52.526 --> 00:40:57.327
But most of your classmates,
friends, feel like that same sentiment or?

00:40:57.394 --> 00:40:58.813
-I would say so. Yeah.
-Okay.

00:40:58.880 --> 00:41:01.072
If you didn't look at any of it, right?

00:41:01.139 --> 00:41:04.900
And we had our day today. We're showing
the real nice stuff, obviously.

00:41:04.967 --> 00:41:09.388
You'd be like everything's great,
people are smiling, holding doors open.

00:41:09.934 --> 00:41:11.588
-Right? 
-Absolutely.

00:41:11.655 --> 00:41:15.978
I don't feel like this
coming apart feeling,

00:41:16.045 --> 00:41:19.113
but then you sort of feel it
in the back of your mind.

00:41:19.180 --> 00:41:21.910
-Like he was saying, like you were saying…
-Nationwide.

00:41:21.977 --> 00:41:24.958
Yeah, right?
I think it's worldwide, to be honest.

00:41:25.025 --> 00:41:27.407
Yeah, It's not just the US.

00:41:27.474 --> 00:41:28.890
Everything feels a bit off.

00:41:28.957 --> 00:41:31.638
At least my international friends
that I've talked to.

00:41:31.705 --> 00:41:32.588
I agree.

00:41:34.110 --> 00:41:37.033
-[Peter] What do I think of the drones?
-Yeah, the drones.

00:41:37.100 --> 00:41:40.484
You know, honestly,
it doesn't get me excited.

00:41:40.551 --> 00:41:41.645
-Really?
-Here's why.

00:41:41.712 --> 00:41:43.586
I don't like things buzzing above me.

00:41:43.653 --> 00:41:44.536
Well…

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:47.434
What's the story here? What's going on?

00:41:47.861 --> 00:41:53.155
Basically, we're contracted with Walmart
and we are delivering product for Walmart

00:41:53.222 --> 00:41:56.968
within a three mile radius
of this neighborhood Walmart.

00:41:57.035 --> 00:41:58.068
-No way.
-Yeah.

00:41:58.621 --> 00:42:00.582
-Okay, so that's happening now.
-Yeah.

00:42:01.004 --> 00:42:02.449
-Wow.
-Yeah, we're live.

00:42:02.516 --> 00:42:03.829
We're live?

00:42:03.896 --> 00:42:05.651
Picking three orders.

00:42:05.718 --> 00:42:07.730
Okay, so the mechanics of this,

00:42:07.797 --> 00:42:11.064
somebody buys something in Walmart online.

00:42:11.513 --> 00:42:16.064
You can either go from the Walmart app
or the Wing app specifically.

00:42:16.131 --> 00:42:18.575
-Okay, you're gonna bring
the product out here

00:42:18.642 --> 00:42:21.150
and attach it to the drone?
Is that how that works?

00:42:21.217 --> 00:42:24.640
Well, yeah, basically an order comes in
and then we have a team

00:42:24.707 --> 00:42:28.310
that picks and packs and then comes out
and then loads the aircraft.

00:42:28.783 --> 00:42:30.812
-And how much weight can that thing fly?

00:42:30.879 --> 00:42:32.904
-About two and a half pounds.

00:42:32.971 --> 00:42:36.052
-Okay, and it goes right to
someone's house on their doorstep?

00:42:36.119 --> 00:42:40.173
Not necessarily on the doorstep,
but it will go to their location.

00:42:40.240 --> 00:42:44.191
When it's descending, it has
obstacle avoidance for trees and stuff.

00:42:44.258 --> 00:42:45.860
It finds a clear spot basically.

00:42:45.927 --> 00:42:48.545
And then it will
with the winch system aligned,

00:42:48.612 --> 00:42:51.477
it will then lower the line
with the package that's on it.

00:42:51.544 --> 00:42:52.493
Okay.

00:42:52.560 --> 00:42:54.758
And then it places it on the ground.

00:42:55.161 --> 00:42:57.543
The hook comes off
and the reel's back up

00:42:57.610 --> 00:43:00.563
and it locks
and then the drone takes back off.

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:02.120
Below 400 feet.

00:43:02.187 --> 00:43:05.566
You can't be higher than 400 feet
when you're flying a drone.

00:43:05.633 --> 00:43:08.181
-That's per FAA.
-Okay.

00:43:08.248 --> 00:43:11.508
-But say you're above my property, right?
-Yes.

00:43:11.575 --> 00:43:14.525
You can't fly a drone
like two feet over my head, obviously.

00:43:14.592 --> 00:43:16.008
-Oh, no.
-What's the minimum?

00:43:16.075 --> 00:43:20.547
For our flight operations,
I mean, takeoff could be,

00:43:20.614 --> 00:43:24.664
you know, 150 feet, something like that.

00:43:24.731 --> 00:43:27.190
When it gets to location and lowers down,

00:43:27.257 --> 00:43:29.737
it doesn't go below 25 feet.

00:43:29.804 --> 00:43:32.541
-Is this getting popular?
-Oh, yeah. Very much so.

00:43:32.608 --> 00:43:34.429
How long you guys been doing it for?

00:43:34.496 --> 00:43:37.063
For here in this area specifically

00:43:37.130 --> 00:43:40.104
with Wing,
Wing's been here for almost a year.

00:43:40.699 --> 00:43:41.582
Here.

00:43:41.649 --> 00:43:45.590
Drone delivery in this area
has been going on for several years now.

00:43:46.288 --> 00:43:47.171
-That's wild.

00:43:47.239 --> 00:43:49.372
Yeah. It's a big thing. It's catching.

00:43:49.439 --> 00:43:51.898
-You're excited?
-I am. I love this.

00:43:51.965 --> 00:43:52.853
It's fascinating.

00:43:52.920 --> 00:43:56.520
Yeah. My background,
I have 20 plus years in IT.

00:43:56.588 --> 00:44:00.124
And when COVID hit,
it locked everything down, right?

00:44:00.191 --> 00:44:02.797
So I'm remoting from the couch and stuff.

00:44:02.864 --> 00:44:05.460
I'm just like, I got to get outside.

00:44:05.527 --> 00:44:06.936
So, I picked up a drone.

00:44:07.003 --> 00:44:10.798
And I got my,
what's called a Part 107 certification.

00:44:10.865 --> 00:44:14.701
It's a requirement for us
to be able to fly commercially.

00:44:14.768 --> 00:44:18.470
So, I got that and then I started flying
that drone around the neighborhood

00:44:18.537 --> 00:44:19.664
to be able to get out.

00:44:19.731 --> 00:44:25.044
And I just liked it so much. I love
the technology and I just pursued that.

00:44:25.111 --> 00:44:27.743
You plug in an address,
they automatically fly there?

00:44:27.810 --> 00:44:29.113
No human is flying it?

00:44:29.180 --> 00:44:34.222
Well, the system,
there is a pilot in command at all times.

00:44:34.289 --> 00:44:36.596
-There's a pilot flying each one?
-Yes.

00:44:36.663 --> 00:44:39.013
-Is he in the Philippines or where?
-No, no, no.

00:44:39.080 --> 00:44:42.239
I mean, of course,
he's not at this location, but it's remote.

00:44:42.306 --> 00:44:45.917
And the pilot will make sure
that the mission,

00:44:45.984 --> 00:44:48.596
the flight operations is fine and stuff.

00:44:48.663 --> 00:44:51.976
And of course, he's able to
make necessary maneuvers.

00:44:52.043 --> 00:44:53.733
-Mission accomplished.
-Yeah.

00:44:53.800 --> 00:44:55.950
So, sitting in
an office building somewhere.

00:44:56.017 --> 00:44:57.255
Well, you know.

00:44:57.322 --> 00:44:59.331
-It's top secret.
-Somewhere. [laughs]

00:44:59.398 --> 00:45:01.240
All right. I appreciate it.

00:45:01.320 --> 00:45:03.255
-No problem.
-All the best.

00:45:03.681 --> 00:45:04.606
Thank you.

00:45:04.673 --> 00:45:07.706
Yeah. I mean,
the technology of it, I think, is cool.

00:45:07.773 --> 00:45:10.142
Look, it's a personal thing,
just like anything.

00:45:10.209 --> 00:45:13.340
I don't know if most people
agree or disagree with me, but…

00:45:13.407 --> 00:45:15.537
-It's all about convenience.
-I get it.

00:45:15.604 --> 00:45:18.063
I just hate hearing those things overhead.

00:45:18.145 --> 00:45:20.354
But some people don't care, I guess.

00:45:20.421 --> 00:45:21.988
-They're not worried about it.

00:45:22.055 --> 00:45:23.905
All right. Where are we going, Jacob?

00:45:23.972 --> 00:45:26.873
We're gonna go to
the University of Arkansas campus.

00:45:26.940 --> 00:45:30.551
Okay. For those that don't know
what a college campus is like these days,

00:45:30.618 --> 00:45:31.512
like myself.

00:45:31.580 --> 00:45:33.923
-We're gonna check it out.
-You're gonna see.

00:45:33.990 --> 00:45:36.211
-It's a booming college campus.
-Booming?

00:45:36.629 --> 00:45:37.930
How many students?

00:45:37.997 --> 00:45:39.573
-35,000.
-Whoa.

00:45:40.190 --> 00:45:41.073
-Big.
-Yeah.

00:45:41.140 --> 00:45:44.114
Which is, like, 20% more
than just a few years ago.

00:45:44.559 --> 00:45:45.442
Wow.

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:51.603
[Peter] So, what I wanted to touch on
before we sort of leave Walmartville,

00:45:51.670 --> 00:45:55.086
the Bentonville that I just experienced

00:45:55.153 --> 00:45:58.498
is not the Walmart experience
you see out in the world as much.

00:45:58.565 --> 00:46:00.036
Like, out in the country.

00:46:00.784 --> 00:46:04.183
And I get it. Walmart is also
a very controversial business

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:09.252
in the sense that a lot of people
attribute it to destroying small towns.

00:46:09.906 --> 00:46:12.289
The Walmart goes in outside of town.

00:46:12.356 --> 00:46:13.239
Yeah.

00:46:13.306 --> 00:46:16.757
The small town
main street shops can't compete.

00:46:16.824 --> 00:46:19.130
-Sure.
-They can't compete on prices.

00:46:19.197 --> 00:46:20.991
You hollow out these towns.

00:46:21.850 --> 00:46:24.075
-It's a double-edged sword.
-It is.

00:46:24.142 --> 00:46:28.050
Because they offer something many parts
of the country, they need those things.

00:46:28.117 --> 00:46:30.173
And they offer amazing prices.

00:46:30.607 --> 00:46:32.371
-But then…
-Becomes more affordable.

00:46:32.438 --> 00:46:37.317
But when it results in the small town
mom-and-pop shops closing,

00:46:38.524 --> 00:46:41.212
you know,
saddens a lot of people, including myself.

00:46:41.279 --> 00:46:43.105
-Yeah.
-So, it's like gentrification.

00:46:43.172 --> 00:46:45.190
-There are two ways to look at it.
-Yeah.

00:46:45.257 --> 00:46:49.196
Depending on where you stand,
it can be a great or a terrible thing.

00:46:49.263 --> 00:46:53.426
And I think Walmart is one of those
controversial-type businesses.

00:46:54.003 --> 00:46:57.025
But you guys are gung-ho Walmart
in this part of the country.

00:46:57.092 --> 00:46:59.471
Like, no matter what, it's amazing

00:46:59.538 --> 00:47:01.688
'cause it's adding so much into your lives.

00:47:01.755 --> 00:47:04.433
It is.
It's made a huge difference on this area.

00:47:04.500 --> 00:47:06.912
And it's just kind of what we're used to.

00:47:06.979 --> 00:47:10.038
Right. So, you see
a whole different perspective than

00:47:10.915 --> 00:47:11.990
a lot of the country.

00:47:12.057 --> 00:47:17.651
If I was that small town shop
in Main Street, USA, tiny, tiny town,

00:47:18.377 --> 00:47:22.154
I'm thinking differently
about Walmart than you guys…

00:47:22.221 --> 00:47:24.644
-…who are getting all the goods of it.
-Sure.

00:47:25.060 --> 00:47:26.883
It's more than just Walmart, though.

00:47:26.950 --> 00:47:29.311
Any company is gonna price them out.

00:47:29.378 --> 00:47:30.446
-Yes.
-Beyond Walmart.

00:47:30.513 --> 00:47:32.963
And that's kind of just
the world that we live in.

00:47:33.030 --> 00:47:33.936
It is.

00:47:34.003 --> 00:47:35.376
There's no turning it back.

00:47:35.443 --> 00:47:38.523
Those small businesses
are gonna struggle no matter what.

00:47:38.590 --> 00:47:41.239
Yeah. It's true.
It's a bit of nostalgia, I guess.

00:47:41.306 --> 00:47:42.933
-Which is hard.
-Right.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:45.125
We kind of have to face the reality of it.

00:47:45.192 --> 00:47:48.359
Those in-person experiences,
like going somewhere to shop,

00:47:48.426 --> 00:47:49.728
are becoming less common.

00:47:49.795 --> 00:47:52.759
I mean, a lot of my friends
deliver groceries to their dorm.

00:47:52.826 --> 00:47:54.440
They don't even go out.

00:47:54.507 --> 00:47:58.414
-Your friends aren't grocery shopping?
-They don't go to the grocery store, no.

00:47:58.481 --> 00:48:01.612
They just order it and it gets delivered,
just like our food.

00:48:01.679 --> 00:48:03.208
What do you think of that?

00:48:04.356 --> 00:48:07.664
I don't know.
I think it just becomes another reason

00:48:07.731 --> 00:48:11.694
that we stay stuck inside our own homes

00:48:11.761 --> 00:48:15.811
and not going out interacting with people,
being in the public.

00:48:15.878 --> 00:48:17.819
Overall, I see it as a bad thing.

00:48:18.313 --> 00:48:21.296
It's kind of this convenience world
that we've created.

00:48:21.363 --> 00:48:23.906
But if people buy it
they're gonna keep building that out.

00:48:23.973 --> 00:48:26.323
-Right.
-So, it's gonna be there no matter what.

00:48:26.390 --> 00:48:29.356
I prefer to just go to the grocery store

00:48:29.772 --> 00:48:31.184
as my family always has.

00:48:31.666 --> 00:48:35.763
I enjoy going to local restaurants.
I don't want to order on my phone.

00:48:37.050 --> 00:48:40.483
-All right. This is all university?
-This is University of Arkansas.

00:48:40.550 --> 00:48:42.373
How much does it cost to go here?

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:46.303
-In-state it's $10,000 a year.
-Okay. That's pretty good.

00:48:46.370 --> 00:48:49.547
Which is pretty affordable
compared to other major universities.

00:48:49.614 --> 00:48:52.508
And then it's about
double that out-of-state.

00:48:52.575 --> 00:48:54.470
I'm gonna take you down Sorority Row.

00:48:54.537 --> 00:48:55.894
They have beautiful houses.

00:48:55.962 --> 00:48:58.682
-Is that where you hang out, Jacob?
-From time to time.

00:48:58.749 --> 00:49:01.323
My girlfriend's in Sorority.
I'll show you her house.

00:49:01.420 --> 00:49:04.008
But, this one's been around for 150 years.

00:49:04.075 --> 00:49:06.183
-Oh, look at these. These are sororities?

00:49:06.250 --> 00:49:08.906
These are sorority houses.
So, students live in there.

00:49:08.973 --> 00:49:10.842
-They're huge. They're like mansions.

00:49:10.909 --> 00:49:11.874
-They're humongous.

00:49:11.941 --> 00:49:14.253
You have to pay a lot extra
to go there, right?

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:16.598
-Thousands a year.
-Thousands. Okay.

00:49:16.665 --> 00:49:19.075
And that's if you're not living there.

00:49:19.142 --> 00:49:21.683
-Look at these gates.
-Those are the Pi Phi gates.

00:49:21.750 --> 00:49:24.558
Kind of like the entrance to university.

00:49:24.625 --> 00:49:26.916
-This is a bougie college, bougie campus.

00:49:26.983 --> 00:49:27.866
It's nice.

00:49:28.337 --> 00:49:29.998
This is my girlfriend's sorority.

00:49:30.065 --> 00:49:30.965
-This one?
-Yep.

00:49:31.032 --> 00:49:33.066
Jeez. How are the rooms inside?

