00:50:44.816 --> 00:50:47.175
-It's got those curtains.
-There's a rooftop.

00:50:47.242 --> 00:50:48.883
-Is this a frat?
-It is.

00:50:50.046 --> 00:50:50.929
That's Kappa Sig.

00:50:51.741 --> 00:50:54.403
Do you guys still do hazing?
Is that a thing?

00:50:54.470 --> 00:50:56.649
You'll have to ask them. I'm not in a frat.

00:50:56.716 --> 00:50:59.793
-But I think it's…
-Jacob, you know the answer.

00:50:59.860 --> 00:51:01.721
I think it's toned down a little bit.

00:51:01.788 --> 00:51:05.683
-It's not as wild as it was.
-It's not like a few decades ago.

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:07.565
Here's our institute of research.

00:51:07.632 --> 00:51:08.746
-This place?
-Yeah.

00:51:08.813 --> 00:51:09.696
Nice.

00:51:10.120 --> 00:51:12.961
-Pretty new building.
When I started, this wasn't here.

00:51:13.028 --> 00:51:15.522
-Is this the biggest campus in the state?

00:51:15.589 --> 00:51:16.783
-For sure. By far.

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:20.086
This is the Clinton House and Museum.

00:51:20.153 --> 00:51:23.676
-Bill Clinton's house?
-You can visit. It's open to the public.

00:51:23.743 --> 00:51:25.458
He lived here when he was younger.

00:51:25.525 --> 00:51:27.516
Okay, why has he got a house on campus?

00:51:27.583 --> 00:51:29.436
These are normal houses now?

00:51:29.503 --> 00:51:32.579
-These are normal houses.
-Okay. So we're right out of campus.

00:51:32.646 --> 00:51:33.893
But these are dorms.

00:51:33.967 --> 00:51:34.850
-Okay.

00:51:35.340 --> 00:51:36.281
Very nice dorms.

00:51:39.526 --> 00:51:41.059
-What's up, guys?
-What's up?

00:51:41.126 --> 00:51:42.714
Good. What's going on here?

00:51:43.804 --> 00:51:45.318
-Crawfish boil.
-Crawfish boil.

00:51:46.492 --> 00:51:49.485
-We're making a video. Is that cool?
-Yeah. You good.

00:51:49.552 --> 00:51:51.670
Your shirt, where you get that from?

00:51:52.860 --> 00:51:55.403
-What do you got?
-Are you recording the campus?

00:51:55.470 --> 00:51:56.843
Crawfish boil.

00:51:56.910 --> 00:51:59.026
Are you guys part of this? You're cooking?

00:51:59.093 --> 00:52:02.068
No. We're not cooking.
We got vendors cooking it.

00:52:02.135 --> 00:52:04.258
-You guys go to university here?
-Yes, sir.

00:52:04.325 --> 00:52:06.118
-Nice. How is it?
-It's fun.

00:52:06.527 --> 00:52:09.413
This is the person
that puts the crawfish boil on.

00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:11.706
-End of year. This is it.
-Yeah. End of year.

00:52:11.773 --> 00:52:13.653
This is the last day of class.

00:52:13.726 --> 00:52:16.024
Jacob, you skipped the last day of class?

00:52:16.091 --> 00:52:18.461
-I did skip the last day of class.
-Nice. Thanks, buddy.

00:52:18.528 --> 00:52:20.693
-But it was worth it.
-Appreciate it.

00:52:20.760 --> 00:52:22.758
-Who's this guy?
-This is Zach.

00:52:22.825 --> 00:52:24.194
-Zach.
-Pleasure to meet you.

00:52:24.261 --> 00:52:25.543
-The legend.
-Yes.

00:52:25.610 --> 00:52:27.460
-That's what they say.
-Living legend.

00:52:27.527 --> 00:52:28.650
The streets say.

00:52:28.717 --> 00:52:31.817
Zach, so last day of school,
your boy didn't show up for class.

00:52:31.884 --> 00:52:33.486
What do you think about that?

00:52:33.553 --> 00:52:35.776
I think that really says a lot
about his work ethic

00:52:35.843 --> 00:52:37.569
and the kind of character that he has.

00:52:37.636 --> 00:52:38.514
It does.

00:52:38.581 --> 00:52:41.151
-I got my stuff figured out.
-All right.

00:52:41.218 --> 00:52:44.995
If you don't figure it out by now
then you're done for finals.

00:52:45.062 --> 00:52:48.162
-Should we go down there, guys?
-Let's go to the Greek Theater.

00:52:48.244 --> 00:52:50.993
-Zack what do you studying?
-Data science.

00:52:51.060 --> 00:52:52.720
All right. How's that going?

00:52:52.787 --> 00:52:55.563
-It's going great.
-Are you gonna work for Walmart?

00:52:56.055 --> 00:52:58.364
-It's a possibility. I'd rather not.
-It is.

00:52:58.431 --> 00:53:01.304
I'm actually more interested in working on

00:53:01.371 --> 00:53:04.726
the complete opposite end
of the spectrum in the startup world.

00:53:04.793 --> 00:53:06.701
Oh, there you go. Like Jacob.

00:53:06.768 --> 00:53:07.762
Yeah. Like Jacob.

00:53:07.829 --> 00:53:10.613
That's actually how
me and Jacob originally met.

00:53:10.680 --> 00:53:11.732
-Oh, that's cool.

00:53:11.799 --> 00:53:13.926
Jacob, why is everyone dressed up?

00:53:13.993 --> 00:53:14.973
It's formal season.

00:53:15.050 --> 00:53:19.077
So a lot of the sororities are gonna have
formals these last few weeks of school.

00:53:19.144 --> 00:53:20.954
They go out and party all together.

00:53:21.021 --> 00:53:22.042
Dress up.

00:53:22.109 --> 00:53:23.595
-It's a thing.
-Do that thing.

00:53:23.662 --> 00:53:25.327
-Do that thing. It's fun.
-Okay.

00:53:25.394 --> 00:53:27.167
They're having a good time already.

00:53:27.234 --> 00:53:30.293
A lot of people come out here
and study when it's nice.

00:53:30.360 --> 00:53:31.243
Okay.

00:53:31.310 --> 00:53:33.839
We have concerts here
for students for free.

00:53:34.825 --> 00:53:37.008
This is kind of one of the meeting places.

00:53:37.075 --> 00:53:39.064
-Okay. One of the hot spots.
-Yeah.

00:53:39.131 --> 00:53:40.563
Are you from Arkansas?

00:53:40.630 --> 00:53:42.203
I was born in Kansas.

00:53:42.270 --> 00:53:43.774
So what's your take on things?

00:53:43.841 --> 00:53:48.135
You seem pretty fired up about life
and work and startups.

00:53:48.202 --> 00:53:50.229
I'm so fired up. I'm obviously biased,

00:53:50.296 --> 00:53:52.414
but I think this is the place to be.

00:53:52.819 --> 00:53:55.786
Especially as far as middle America goes,

00:53:55.853 --> 00:53:58.440
you know, from my perspective

00:53:58.507 --> 00:54:01.518
in the work that I do,
and I'm sure Jacob can attest to this,

00:54:01.585 --> 00:54:03.302
we get labeled as a flyover state.

00:54:03.369 --> 00:54:06.863
-Yeah.
-Or "emerging market", quote unquote.

00:54:06.930 --> 00:54:09.863
And I think that kind of
extends past just business.

00:54:09.930 --> 00:54:14.151
I think it can be said of
a lot of like social trends.

00:54:14.218 --> 00:54:15.101
Okay.

00:54:15.801 --> 00:54:16.684
And education.

00:54:16.751 --> 00:54:19.351
-But you don't agree with it?
-I don't agree with it.

00:54:19.418 --> 00:54:22.925
I'm fortunate enough to get to see
a very cool side of what's going on.

00:54:22.992 --> 00:54:27.062
I think there are a lot of people that are
finding what they like to do

00:54:27.129 --> 00:54:29.340
and how they can make an impact
in the world,

00:54:29.407 --> 00:54:31.952
both locally, regionally, here in Arkansas,

00:54:32.019 --> 00:54:35.415
especially in the Fayetteville,
Bentonville area, and beyond.

00:54:35.482 --> 00:54:39.543
I will say a big part of that is because of
the companies like Walmart.

00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:42.993
I feel like there's so much talent,
curiosity, and creativity here.

00:54:43.060 --> 00:54:46.127
And people are like finally
starting to get that edge to them.

00:54:46.194 --> 00:54:49.645
Like, oh, I want to do this.
I want to make something happen.

00:54:49.712 --> 00:54:52.376
From the outside,
if you're looking at the Internet,

00:54:52.443 --> 00:54:54.743
maybe not the best way
to understand the world.

00:54:54.810 --> 00:54:58.821
I try to grab the real life and put it
on the Internet, but most of the Internet,

00:54:58.888 --> 00:55:03.340
a lot of it is made for clickbait,
trigger emotions, dopamine.

00:55:03.407 --> 00:55:05.971
If you're to be in that world, you'd think

00:55:06.038 --> 00:55:10.183
the younger 20,
mid 20 somethings, men especially,

00:55:10.250 --> 00:55:12.911
doom and gloom, no opportunity,

00:55:13.715 --> 00:55:16.813
they're all crying in their pillows,
but you're saying no.

00:55:17.670 --> 00:55:18.553
I say no.

00:55:19.265 --> 00:55:24.411
And I think that's a subjective choice that
every individual has to make to an extent.

00:55:24.478 --> 00:55:28.597
And I think you can find
doom and gloom anywhere in the world,

00:55:28.664 --> 00:55:32.807
but I will say it's admittedly easier
when you're in a more impoverished,

00:55:32.874 --> 00:55:36.118
less educated,
less progressive state around here.

00:55:36.185 --> 00:55:39.091
There may be more to be gloomy about,

00:55:39.158 --> 00:55:43.393
but that being said,
there is so, so much out here that…

00:55:43.460 --> 00:55:46.450
-When you're in this environment
that I've seen today, it's like…

00:55:46.517 --> 00:55:49.726
It'd be harder to be all bummed out 'cause
it looks like there's a lot happening.

00:55:49.793 --> 00:55:51.279
Oh my gosh, yes.

00:55:51.346 --> 00:55:53.396
And look at how beautiful this campus is.

00:55:53.463 --> 00:55:56.606
-You have a stunning campus.
-It is beautiful.

00:55:57.685 --> 00:56:01.957
There's an out-of-state enrollment,
I don't want to say problem,

00:56:02.024 --> 00:56:04.843
but some sort of controversy here.

00:56:05.550 --> 00:56:10.213
I would go so far as to say
most of this campus is not from Arkansas.

00:56:10.614 --> 00:56:12.600
They're from Texas, Missouri.

00:56:13.500 --> 00:56:14.982
Okay, so what's the problem?

00:56:15.360 --> 00:56:17.680
The problem is there's a question of if…

00:56:18.117 --> 00:56:21.747
There's already been a question
that does University of Arkansas cater to

00:56:21.814 --> 00:56:24.413
a very small part of
the Arkansas population,

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:26.282
being in this Northwest world?

00:56:26.349 --> 00:56:29.216
-Abandoning the rest of the state.
-The rest of the state.

00:56:29.283 --> 00:56:32.411
Why, because they don't have
the grades to get in here or what?

00:56:32.478 --> 00:56:35.178
You're just picking people
with the best grades, right?

00:56:35.245 --> 00:56:37.425
Uh-huh. And it's also a funding problem,

00:56:37.492 --> 00:56:40.439
and the university is working a lot
to counter that.

00:56:40.506 --> 00:56:42.566
Oh, out-of-state tuition versus in-state.

00:56:42.633 --> 00:56:43.623
-Yes.
-Got you.

00:56:43.690 --> 00:56:47.423
All right, are we crashing the party?
-You can crash the party if you want to.

00:56:47.490 --> 00:56:49.689
-This is a big deal.
-This is over the top.

00:56:49.756 --> 00:56:51.782
So we're catching it at the right time.

00:56:51.849 --> 00:56:54.755
-[woman] Are we vlogging?
-We're vlogging.  Do you want to jump in?

00:56:54.822 --> 00:56:57.423
-Yes!
-Okay, what's going on, you guys?

00:56:57.490 --> 00:56:59.429
Welcome to the University of Arkansas.

00:56:59.496 --> 00:57:01.546
-This is our spring formal.
-We're freshmen.

00:57:01.613 --> 00:57:03.928
-You're freshmen.
Okay, it's gonna go by quick.

00:57:03.995 --> 00:57:05.889
Just want to let you know that.
So have a good time.

00:57:05.956 --> 00:57:07.856
-You're Peter?
-Yeah. What's your name?

00:57:07.923 --> 00:57:09.062
-I'm Knox.
-Knox!

00:57:09.129 --> 00:57:11.587
-I love your stuff, man.
-Thanks. I appreciate it.

00:57:11.654 --> 00:57:15.059
One of my favorites was Alabama.
Fairhope, that was awesome.

00:57:15.126 --> 00:57:18.842
-Okay, what's going on right now?
-So it's a sorority formal.

00:57:18.909 --> 00:57:21.814
And basically what you do is
like homecoming or prom.

00:57:21.881 --> 00:57:26.446
You just dress up, go on a date.
Maybe you eat, maybe you don't.

00:57:26.513 --> 00:57:29.824
They're all taking pictures,
and then we'll go to like a hotel or…

00:57:29.891 --> 00:57:31.851
-Do you got a date tonight?
-I do. Yeah.

00:57:31.918 --> 00:57:34.112
-Are you pretty pumped?
-I am pretty pumped. She's cool.

00:57:34.179 --> 00:57:37.079
-First date?
-Friends of friends. Yeah, all good.

00:57:37.146 --> 00:57:39.286
-It's a friend.
-Yeah for now. Who knows?

00:57:39.353 --> 00:57:41.399
-So you might…
-Who knows? Yeah.

00:57:41.466 --> 00:57:45.071
By the time this video goes out,
we'll know if you crossed a line or not.

00:57:45.138 --> 00:57:47.113
-How long does it usually take?
-A few weeks.

00:57:47.180 --> 00:57:49.498
Thanks for watching.
I appreciate you, brother.

00:57:49.565 --> 00:57:51.187
Good luck with everything.

00:57:51.254 --> 00:57:53.753
-Have fun tonight, man.
-Yeah, enjoy the night.

00:57:54.550 --> 00:57:57.527
So these are all sorority members, right?

00:57:57.594 --> 00:57:58.787
-Yeah.
-Okay.

00:57:58.854 --> 00:58:00.612
Their dates don't have to be.

00:58:00.679 --> 00:58:03.029
Okay, the dates…
So like me, I'm not in a frat.

00:58:03.096 --> 00:58:05.625
-Where are all the guys?
That's the question.

00:58:06.352 --> 00:58:07.933
-They're doing their own thing.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:11.472
Where are the dates?
They're supposed to be taking pictures.

00:58:11.539 --> 00:58:13.152
-All right.
-They should be here.

00:58:13.219 --> 00:58:15.296
This guy's rocking it. Look at this guy.

00:58:15.363 --> 00:58:19.953
Dude, I just got to commend you
for rocking the middle part in the stash.

00:58:20.020 --> 00:58:22.345
-Dude, it looks good.
-Thanks, man.

00:58:22.412 --> 00:58:25.446
-Have fun. Live this up.
-We're a thruple right here.

00:58:25.513 --> 00:58:27.157
-The thruple?
-Yes, the thruple.

00:58:27.224 --> 00:58:29.830
-You two…
-I just met them.

00:58:29.897 --> 00:58:31.706
-It's me and her and then…

00:58:31.774 --> 00:58:32.657
Okay.

00:58:33.900 --> 00:58:36.746
It's a lot of polyamory here?
Is that what you're saying?

00:58:36.813 --> 00:58:38.952
-Polygamy, too.
-Polygamy.

00:58:39.019 --> 00:58:43.200
90% of the U of A campus
around here is very polygamous.

00:58:43.267 --> 00:58:45.267
-I've read that.
-Yeah.

00:58:45.334 --> 00:58:47.547
The statistics are pretty…

00:58:47.614 --> 00:58:50.883
-Are there some cult vibes around here?
-Oh, yeah. Definitely.

00:58:50.950 --> 00:58:52.437
Yeah. A little bit. Okay.

00:58:52.504 --> 00:58:54.567
Being a Hog fan is like a cult, really.

00:58:54.634 --> 00:58:56.123
I wish I was a Hog fan.

00:58:56.190 --> 00:58:57.213
Are you guys from Arkansas?

00:58:57.280 --> 00:58:58.868
I'm from…

00:58:58.935 --> 00:58:59.818
[Peter] Oh!

00:59:00.532 --> 00:59:02.650
[loud music coming from motorcycle]

00:59:03.412 --> 00:59:04.706
[Peter] Yeah, brother!

00:59:04.773 --> 00:59:06.453
[bike revs and speeds off]

00:59:08.563 --> 00:59:09.827
Did you guys see that?

00:59:09.894 --> 00:59:12.333
He just lifted the back end
of a motorcycle up.

00:59:12.400 --> 00:59:15.416
That was the most
Chicano thing I've ever seen.

00:59:15.483 --> 00:59:17.353
There's a good Chicano population.

00:59:17.420 --> 00:59:20.576
-Are you serious?
-Especially in Springdale.

00:59:20.643 --> 00:59:23.056
-You got lowriders?
-Yeah. Oh, there's lowriders.

00:59:23.123 --> 00:59:25.463
I've done a bunch of videos
with those guys.

00:59:25.530 --> 00:59:27.141
-Are you serious?
-Yeah. East LA.

00:59:27.208 --> 00:59:28.690
Oh, dude. That's awesome.

00:59:28.757 --> 00:59:31.503
That's like the capital
of the United States.

00:59:31.570 --> 00:59:32.717
I went in deep.

00:59:33.160 --> 00:59:36.690
This is wild. You guys are having fun.
Why don't you guys get in there?

00:59:36.757 --> 00:59:39.007
I already did it.
This is a weeks long thing.

00:59:39.074 --> 00:59:42.634
-It's a week's long?
-They can't do it all at once

00:59:42.701 --> 00:59:44.719
or Fayetteville would explode.

00:59:44.786 --> 00:59:48.449
-It would just blow up.
-They can't book all the places at once.

00:59:48.865 --> 00:59:50.935
-They got like a schedule going.
-Yeah.

00:59:51.310 --> 00:59:52.792
[students chattering]

00:59:55.630 --> 00:59:58.195
Your campus is like
a European city or something.

00:59:58.262 --> 01:00:00.853
-It's beautiful.
-Like a beautiful European city.

01:00:00.920 --> 01:00:03.673
-Look at these buildings and these squares.
-Yeah.

01:00:03.750 --> 01:00:05.985
This is the oldest building on campus.

01:00:06.606 --> 01:00:08.126
It's called Old Main.

01:00:08.193 --> 01:00:10.575
At one point was the only building, right?

01:00:10.642 --> 01:00:13.728
-Yeah. This was the whole campus
starting out right here.

01:00:14.681 --> 01:00:17.121
If you see the two clock towers,

01:00:17.188 --> 01:00:20.364
the one facing north
is a little higher than the south.

01:00:20.431 --> 01:00:23.650
And there's an urban legend
that that's because the

01:00:24.264 --> 01:00:27.784
Northwest Arkansas community
supported the North in the Civil War

01:00:27.851 --> 01:00:29.927
while the rest of the state
supported the South.

01:00:29.994 --> 01:00:31.103
-Interesting.

01:00:31.170 --> 01:00:35.496
I don't know if I have a source on that,
but it's what people say.

01:00:35.563 --> 01:00:39.847
Historians are gonna be all over you
in the comments for that claim.

01:00:39.914 --> 01:00:41.494
Uh-huh. They can attack me.

